# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: general-relativity
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:general-relativity/curvature] In mathematics, **curvature** is any of several strongly related concepts in geometry that intuitively measure the amount by which a curve deviates from being a straight line or by which a surface deviates from being a plane.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] If a curve or surface is contained in a larger space, curvature can be defined *extrinsically* relative to the ambient space.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Curvature of Riemannian manifolds of dimension at least two can be defined *intrinsically* without reference to a larger space.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] For curves, curvature describes how sharply the curve bends.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The canonical examples are circles: smaller circles bend more sharply and hence have higher curvature.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] For a point on a general curve, the direction of the curve is described by its tangent line.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] How sharply the curve is bending at that point can be measured by how much that tangent line changes direction per unit distance along the curve.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Curvature measures the angular rate of change of the direction of the tangent line, or the unit tangent vector, of the curve per unit distance along the curve.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Curvature is expressed in units of radians per unit distance.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] For a circle, that rate of change is the same at all points on the circle and is equal to the reciprocal of the circle's radius.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Straight lines don't change direction and have zero curvature.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The curvature at a point on a twice differentiable curve is the magnitude of its curvature vector at that point and is also the curvature of its osculating circle, which is the circle that best approximates the curve near that point.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] For surfaces (and, more generally for higher-dimensional manifolds), that are embedded in a Euclidean space, the concept of curvature is more complex, as it depends on the choice of a direction on the surface or manifold.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] This leads to the concepts of *maximal curvature*, *minimal curvature*, and *mean curvature*.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The history of curvature began with the ancient Greeks' basic distinction between straight and circular lines, with the concept later developed by figures like Aristotle and Apollonius.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The development of calculus in the 17th century, particularly by Newton and Leibniz, provided tools to systematically calculate curvature for curves.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Euler then extended the study to surfaces, followed by Gauss's crucial insight of "intrinsic" curvature, which is independent of how a surface is embedded in space, and Riemann's generalization to higher dimensions.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The curvature of a differentiable curve was originally defined through osculating circles.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] In this setting, Augustin-Louis Cauchy showed that the center of curvature is the intersection point of two infinitely close normal lines to the curve.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Intuitively, curvature describes for any part of a curve how much the curve direction changes over a small distance along the curve.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The direction of the curve at any point **P** is described by a unit tangent vector, **T**.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] A section of a curve is also called an arc, and length along the curve is arc length, s.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] So the curvature for a small section of the curve is the angle of the change of the direction of the tangent vector divided by the arc length Δs.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] For a general curve which might have a varying curvature along its length, the curvature at a point **P** on the curve is the limit of the curvature of sections containing **P** as the length of the sections approaches zero.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] For a twice differentiable curve, that limit is the magnitude of the derivative of the unit tangent vector with respect to arc length.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Curvature is a differential-geometric property of the curve; it does not depend on the parametrization of the curve.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] In particular, it does not depend on the orientation of the parametrized curve, i.e. which direction along the curve is associated with increasing parameter values.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] A curve that is parametrized by arc length is a vector-valued function that is denoted by the Greek letter gamma with an overbar, –***γ***, that describes the position of a point on the curve, P, in terms of its arc-length distance, s along the curve from some other reference point on the curve.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The parameter s can also be interpreted as a time parameter.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Then –***γ***(s) describes the path of a particle that moves along the curve at a constant unit speed.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Curvature can then be understood as a measure of how fast the direction of the particle rotates.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] A twice differentiable curve, ***γ***: [*a*, *b*] → $\mathbb {R}$ *n*, that is not parametrized by arc length can be re-parametrized by arc length provided that ***γ***′(t) is everywhere not zero, so that 1/‖***γ***′(t)‖ is always a finite positive number.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Both ***γ*** and –***γ*** trace the same path in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ and so have the same curvature vector and curvature at each point **P** on the curve.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] This is also reflected in the second expression for the curvature: the expression inside the parentheses is cos *θ*, where θ is the angle between the vectors **T** and ***γ***′′(*t*), so that the square root produces sin *θ*.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] If **γ** is twice continuously differentiable, then so is s(t) and –**γ**, while ***T***(*t*) is continuously differentiable, and ***K***(*t*) and *κ*(*t*) are continuous.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Often it is difficult or impossible to express the arc-length parametrization, –***γ***, in closed form even when **γ** is given in closed form.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] This is typically the case when it is difficult or impossible to express *s*(*t*) or its inverse *t*(*s*) in closed form.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] However curvature can be expressed only in terms of the first and second derivatives of **γ**, without direct reference to –***γ***.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The curvature vector represents both the direction towards which the curve is turning as well as how sharply it turns.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Historically, the curvature of a differentiable curve was defined through the osculating circle, which is the circle that best approximates the curve at a point.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] More precisely, given a point **P** on a curve, every other point **Q** of the curve defines a circle (or sometimes a line) passing through **Q** and tangent to the curve at **P**.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The osculating circle is the limit, if it exists, of this circle when **Q** tends to **P**.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Then the *center of curvature* and the *radius of curvature* of the curve at **P** are the center and the radius of the osculating circle.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] When the curvature is zero, for example on a straight line or at a point of inflection, the radius of curvature is infinite and the center of curvature is indeterminate or "at infinity".
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Given two points **P** and **Q** on a curve **γ**, let *s*(**P**,**Q**) be the arc length of the portion of the curve between **P** and **Q** and let *d*(**P**,**Q**) denote the length of the line segment from **P** to **Q**.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] where the limit is taken as the point **Q** approaches **P** on **γ**.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The denominator can equally well be taken to be *d*(***P***,***Q***)3.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The formula follows by verifying it for the osculating circle.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] There may be some situations where the preconditions for the above formulas do not apply, but where it is still appropriate to apply the concept of curvature.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] It can be useful to apply the concept of curvature to a curve **γ** at a point ***P*** = ***γ***(*t0*) if the one-sided derivatives for ***γ***′(*t0*) exist but are different values, or likewise for ***γ***′′(*t0*).
[src:general-relativity/curvature] In such a case, it could be useful to describe the curve with curvature at each side.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Such might be the case of a curve that is constructed piecewise.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Another situation occurs when the limit of a ratio results in an indeterminate 0 / 0 value for the curvature, for example when both derivatives exist but are both zero.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] In such a case, it might be possible to evaluate the underlying limit using l'Hôpital's rule.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The following are examples of curves with application of the relevant concepts and formulas.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] A geometric explanation for why the curvature of a circle of radius *R* at any point **P** is 1/*R* is partially illustrated by the diagram to the right.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The length of the red arc is L and the measure in radians of the arc's central angle, angle ACB, is *L*/*R*.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The angle between the arc endpoint tangents is angle BDE, which is the same size as the central angle, because both angles are supplementary to angle BDA.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The ratio of the angle between the arc endpoint tangents, measured in radians, divided by the arc length L is (*L*/*R*)/*L* = 1/*R*.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Since the ratio is 1/*R* for any arc of the circle that is less than a half circle, for arcs containing any given point **P** on the circle, the limit of the ratio as arc length approaches zero is also 1/*R*.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Hence the curvature of the circle at any point **P** is 1/*R*.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] A common parametrization of a circle of radius r is ***γ***(*t*) = (*r* cos *t*, *r* sin *t*).
[src:general-relativity/curvature] It follows, as expected, that the radius of curvature is the radius of the circle, and that the center of curvature is the center of the circle.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The same circle can also be defined by the implicit equation *F*(*x*, *y*) = 0 with *F*(*x*, *y*) = *x*2 + *y*2 – *r*2.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Consider the parabola *y* = *ax*2 + *bx* + *c*.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] It is the graph of a function, with derivative 2*ax* + *b*, and second derivative 2*a*.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] This means that, if *a* > 0, the concavity is upward directed everywhere; if *a* < 0, the concavity is downward directed; for *a* = 0, the curvature is zero everywhere, confirming that the parabola degenerates into a line in this case.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The (unsigned) curvature is maximal for *x* = –⁠*b*/2*a*⁠, that is at the stationary point (zero derivative) of the function, which is the vertex of the parabola.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The first derivative of x is 1, and the second derivative is zero.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Substituting into the formula for general parametrizations gives exactly the same result as above, with x replaced by t and with primes referring to derivatives with respect to the parameter t.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The same parabola can also be defined by the implicit equation *F*(*x*, *y*) = 0 with *F*(*x*, *y*) = *ax*2 + *bx* + *c* – *y*.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] As *Fy* = –1, and *Fyy* = *Fxy* = 0, one obtains exactly the same value for the (unsigned) curvature.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] However, the signed curvature is not defined for an implicit equation since the signed curvature depends on an orientation of the curve that is not provided by the implicit equation.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Let ***γ***(*t*) = (*x*(*t*), *y*(*t*)) be a proper parametric representation of a twice differentiable plane curve.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Here *proper* means that on the domain of definition of the parametrization, the derivative ⁠d***γ***/d*t*⁠ exists and is nowhere equal to the zero vector.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] where primes refer to derivatives with respect to t.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] where the numerator is the absolute value of the determinant of the 2-by-2 matrix with **γ**′ and **γ**′′ as the columns.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] These formulas can be understood as an application of the cross product formula for curvature in three dimensions.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Since the operands have zeros in the third dimension, the cross product result will have zero values for the first two dimensions, so only the value in the third dimension is relevant to calculating the magnitude of the cross product.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The formula for the value of the third dimension thus appears in the numerator of the above formulas.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] For plane curves, it can be useful to express the curvature as a single scalar that can be positive or negative, called the **signed curvature** or **oriented curvature** and denoted with a lowercase k.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Whether k is positive or negative depends on the orientation of the curve.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Whether a positive k corresponds to clockwise or counterclockwise turning depends on the orientation of the curve and the orientation of the coordinate axes.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] With a standard orientation of the coordinate axes, when moving along the curve in the direction of increasing t, k is positive if the curve turns to the left, counterclockwise, and it is negative if the curve turns to the right, clockwise.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] This is consistent with the convention of treating counterclockwise rotations as rotations through a positive angle.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] However, since the sign of k is dependent on the orientation of the parametrization, k is not differential-geometric property property of the curve.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Except for orientation issues, the signed curvature for a plane curve captures similar information as the curvature vector, which for a plane curve is constrained to just one dimension, the line that is perpendicular to the unit tangent vector.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Using a standard orientation of the coordinate axes, let —**N** be the unit normal vector obtained from the unit tangent vector, **T**, by a counterclockwise rotation of ⁠π/2⁠.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Then —**N** is dependent on the orientation of the curve and points to the left when moving along the curve in the direction of increasing *t*.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] In the general case of a curve, the sign of the signed curvature is somewhat arbitrary, as it depends on the orientation of the curve.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] In the case of the graph of a function, there is a natural orientation by increasing values of x.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] This gives additional significance to the sign of the signed curvature.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The sign of the signed curvature is the same as the sign of the second derivative of f.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] If it is positive then the graph has an upward concavity, and, if it is negative the graph has a downward concavity.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] If it is zero, then one has an inflection point or an undulation point.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] When the slope of the graph (that is the derivative of the function) is small, the signed curvature is well approximated by the second derivative.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] It is common in physics and engineering to approximate the curvature with the second derivative, for example, in beam theory or for deriving the wave equation of a string under tension, and other applications where small slopes are involved.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] This often allows systems that are otherwise nonlinear to be treated approximately as linear.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The signed curvature is not defined, as it depends on an orientation of the curve that is not provided by the implicit equation.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Note that changing F into –*F* would not change the curve defined by *F*(*x*, *y*) = 0, but it would change the sign of the numerator if the absolute value were omitted in the preceding formula.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] A point of the curve where *Fx* = *Fy* = 0 is a singular point, which means that the curve is not differentiable at this point, and thus that the curvature is not defined (most often, the point is either a crossing point or a cusp).
[src:general-relativity/curvature] A *curvature comb* can be used to represent graphically the curvature of every point on a curve.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Curvature combs are useful when combining two different curves in CAD environments.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] They provide a visual representation of the continuity between the curves.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The continuity can be defined as being in one of four levels.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] G0 : The 2 curvature combs are at an angle at the junction.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] G1 : The teeth of the 2 combs are parallel at the junction but are of different length.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] G2 : The teeth are parallel and of the same length.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] However the tangents of the 2 combs are not the same.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] G3 : The teeth are parallel and of the same length and the tangents of the 2 combs are the same.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The above image shows a G2 continuity at the 2 junctions.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] For a general parametrization by a parameter t, one needs expressions involving derivatives with respect to t.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] where the prime denotes differentiation with respect to the parameter t.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] These formulas are related to the general formulas for curvature and the curvature vector, except that they use the vector cross product instead of the scalar dot product to express the perpendicular component of ***γ***′′ / ‖***γ***′‖^2 relative to ***γ***′.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The curvature of curves drawn on a surface is the main tool for the defining and studying the curvature of the surface.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Any non-singular curve on a smooth surface has its tangent vector **T** contained in the tangent plane of the surface.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Let the curve be arc-length parametrized, and let **t** = **u** × **T** so that **T**, **t**, **u** form an orthonormal basis, called the **Darboux frame**.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] All curves on the surface with the same tangent vector at a given point will have the same normal curvature, which is the same as the curvature of the curve obtained by intersecting the surface with the plane containing **T** and **u**.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Taking all possible tangent vectors, the maximum and minimum values of the normal curvature at a point are called the **principal curvatures**, *k*1 and *k*2, and the directions of the corresponding tangent vectors are called **principal normal directions**.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Curvature can be evaluated along surface normal sections, similar to § Curves on surfaces above (see for example the Earth radius of curvature).
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Some curved surfaces, such as those made from a smooth sheet of paper, can be flattened down into the plane without distorting their intrinsic features in any way.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Such developable surfaces have zero Gaussian curvature (see below).
[src:general-relativity/curvature] In contrast to curves, which do not have intrinsic curvature, but do have extrinsic curvature (they only have a curvature given an embedding), surfaces can have intrinsic curvature, independent of an embedding.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The Gaussian curvature, named after Carl Friedrich Gauss, is equal to the product of the principal curvatures, *k*1*k*2.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] It has a dimension of length−2 and is positive for spheres, negative for one-sheet hyperboloids and zero for planes and cylinders.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] It determines whether a surface is locally convex (when it is positive) or locally saddle-shaped (when it is negative).
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Gaussian curvature is an *intrinsic* property of the surface, meaning it does not depend on the particular embedding of the surface; intuitively, this means that ants living on the surface could determine the Gaussian curvature.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] For example, an ant living on a sphere could measure the sum of the interior angles of a triangle and determine that it was greater than 180 degrees, implying that the space it inhabited had positive curvature.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] On the other hand, an ant living on a cylinder would not detect any such departure from Euclidean geometry; in particular the ant could not detect that the two surfaces have different mean curvatures (see below), which is a purely extrinsic type of curvature.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Formally, Gaussian curvature only depends on the Riemannian metric of the surface.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] This is Gauss's celebrated Theorema Egregium, which he found while concerned with geographic surveys and mapmaking.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] An intrinsic definition of the Gaussian curvature at a point P is the following: imagine an ant which is tied to P with a short thread of length r.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] It runs around P while the thread is completely stretched and measures the length *C*(*r*) of one complete trip around P.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] If the surface were flat, the ant would find *C*(*r*) = 2π*r*.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The integral of the Gaussian curvature over the whole surface is closely related to the surface's Euler characteristic; see the Gauss–Bonnet theorem.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The discrete analog of curvature, corresponding to curvature being concentrated at a point and particularly useful for polyhedra, is the (angular) defect; the analog for the Gauss–Bonnet theorem is Descartes' theorem on total angular defect.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Because (Gaussian) curvature can be defined without reference to an embedding space, it is not necessary that a surface be embedded in a higher-dimensional space in order to be curved.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Such an intrinsically curved two-dimensional surface is a simple example of a Riemannian manifold.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The mean curvature is an *extrinsic* measure of curvature equal to half the sum of the principal curvatures, ⁠*k*1 + *k*2/2⁠.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] It was introduced by Sophie Germain in her work on elasticity theory.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Mean curvature is closely related to the first variation of surface area.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] In particular, a minimal surface such as a soap film has mean curvature zero and a soap bubble has constant mean curvature.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Unlike Gauss curvature, the mean curvature is extrinsic and depends on the embedding, for instance, a cylinder and a plane are locally isometric but the mean curvature of a plane is zero while that of a cylinder is nonzero.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The intrinsic and extrinsic curvature of a surface can be combined in the second fundamental form.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] where **N** is the unit normal to the surface.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] For unit tangent vectors **X**, the second fundamental form assumes the maximum value *k*1 and minimum value *k*2, which occur in the principal directions **u**1 and **u**2, respectively.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Thus the second fundamental form encodes both the intrinsic and extrinsic curvatures.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] An encapsulation of surface curvature can be found in the shape operator, *S*, which is a self-adjoint linear operator from the tangent plane to itself (specifically, the differential of the Gauss map).
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The principal curvatures are the eigenvalues of the shape operator, the principal curvature directions are its eigenvectors, the Gauss curvature is its determinant, and the mean curvature is half its trace.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] By extension of the former argument, a space of three or more dimensions can be intrinsically curved.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The curvature is *intrinsic* in the sense that it is a property defined at every point in the space, rather than a property defined with respect to a larger space that contains it.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] In general, a curved space may or may not be conceived as being embedded in a higher-dimensional ambient space; if not then its curvature can only be defined intrinsically.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] In the theory of general relativity, which describes gravity and cosmology, the idea is slightly generalised to the "curvature of spacetime"; in relativity theory spacetime is a pseudo-Riemannian manifold.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Once a time coordinate is defined, the three-dimensional space corresponding to a particular time is generally a curved Riemannian manifold; but since the time coordinate choice is largely arbitrary, it is the underlying spacetime curvature that is physically significant.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] A positive curvature corresponds to the inverse square radius of curvature; an example is a sphere or hypersphere.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] An example of negatively curved space is hyperbolic geometry (see also: non-positive curvature).
[src:general-relativity/curvature] A space or space-time with zero curvature is called ***flat***.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] For example, Euclidean space is an example of a flat space, and Minkowski space is an example of a flat spacetime.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] There are other examples of flat geometries in both settings, though.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] A torus or a cylinder can both be given flat metrics, but differ in their topology.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Other topologies are also possible for curved space .
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The mathematical notion of *curvature* is also defined in much more general contexts.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Many of these generalizations emphasize different aspects of the curvature as it is understood in lower dimensions.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The curvature of a curve can naturally be considered as a kinematic quantity, representing the force felt by a certain observer moving along the curve; analogously, curvature in higher dimensions can be regarded as a kind of tidal force (this is one way of thinking of the sectional curvature).
[src:general-relativity/curvature] This generalization of curvature depends on how nearby test particles diverge or converge when they are allowed to move freely in the space; see Jacobi field.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Another broad generalization of curvature comes from the study of parallel transport on a surface.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] For instance, if a vector is moved around a loop on the surface of a sphere keeping parallel throughout the motion, then the final position of the vector may not be the same as the initial position of the vector.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Various generalizations capture in an abstract form this idea of curvature as a measure of holonomy; see curvature form.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] A closely related notion of curvature comes from gauge theory in physics, where the curvature represents a field and a vector potential for the field is a quantity that is in general path-dependent: it may change if an observer moves around a loop.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Two more generalizations of curvature are the scalar curvature and Ricci curvature.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] In a curved surface such as the sphere, the area of a disc on the surface differs from the area of a disc of the same radius in flat space.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] This difference (in a suitable limit) is measured by the scalar curvature.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The difference in area of a sector of the disc is measured by the Ricci curvature.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Each of the scalar curvature and Ricci curvature are defined in analogous ways in three and higher dimensions.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] They are particularly important in relativity theory, where they both appear on the side of Einstein's field equations that represents the geometry of spacetime (the other side of which represents the presence of matter and energy).
[src:general-relativity/curvature] These generalizations of curvature underlie, for instance, the notion that curvature can be a property of a measure; see curvature of a measure.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Another generalization of curvature relies on the ability to compare a curved space with another space that has *constant* curvature.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] Often this is done with triangles in the spaces.
[src:general-relativity/curvature] The notion of a triangle makes senses in metric spaces, and this gives rise to CAT(*k*) spaces.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] In the general theory of relativity, the **Einstein field equations** (**EFE**; also known as **Einstein's equations**) relate the geometry of spacetime to the distribution of matter-energy within it.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] The equations were published by Albert Einstein in 1915 in the form of a tensor equation which related the local *spacetime curvature* (expressed by the Einstein tensor) with the local energy, momentum and stress within that spacetime (expressed by the stress–energy tensor).
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] The relationship between the metric tensor and the Einstein tensor allows the EFE to be written as a set of nonlinear partial differential equations when used in this way.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] The solutions of the EFE are the components of the metric tensor.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] The inertial trajectories of particles and radiation (geodesics) in the resulting geometry are then calculated using the geodesic equation.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] As well as implying local energy–momentum conservation, the EFE reduce to Newton's law of gravitation in the limit of a weak gravitational field and velocities that are much less than the speed of light.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] Exact solutions for the EFE can only be found under simplifying assumptions such as symmetry.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] Special classes of exact solutions are most often studied since they model many gravitational phenomena, such as rotating black holes and the expanding universe.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] Further simplification is achieved in approximating the spacetime as having only small deviations from flat spacetime, leading to the linearized EFE.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] These equations are used to study phenomena such as gravitational waves.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] where $G_{\mu \nu }$ is the Einstein tensor, $g_{\mu \nu }$ is the metric tensor, $T_{\mu \nu }$ is the stress–energy tensor, $\Lambda$ is the cosmological constant and $\kappa$ is the Einstein gravitational constant.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] where $R_{\mu \nu }$ is the Ricci curvature tensor, and R is the scalar curvature.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] This is a symmetric divergenceless second-degree tensor that depends on only the metric tensor and its first and second derivatives.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] where G is the Newtonian constant of gravitation and c is the speed of light in vacuum.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] In standard units, each term on the left has quantity dimension of L−2.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] The expression on the left represents the curvature of spacetime as determined by the metric; the expression on the right represents the stress–energy–momentum content of spacetime.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] The EFE can then be interpreted as a set of equations dictating how stress–energy–momentum determines the curvature of spacetime.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] These equations form the core of the mathematical formulation of general relativity.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] They readily imply the geodesic equation, which dictates how freely falling test objects move through spacetime.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] The EFE is a tensor equation relating a set of symmetric 4 × 4 tensors.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] Each tensor has 10 independent components.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] The four Bianchi identities reduce the number of independent equations from 10 to 6, leaving the metric with four gauge-fixing degrees of freedom, which correspond to the freedom to choose a coordinate system.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] Although the Einstein field equations were initially formulated in the context of a four-dimensional theory, some theorists have explored their consequences in n dimensions.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] The equations in contexts outside of general relativity are still referred to as the Einstein field equations.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] The vacuum field equations (obtained when $T_{\mu \nu }$ is everywhere zero) define Einstein manifolds.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] The equations are more complex than they appear.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] Given a specified distribution of matter and energy in the form of a stress–energy tensor, the EFE are understood to be equations for the metric tensor $g_{\mu \nu }$ , since both the Ricci tensor and scalar curvature depend on the metric in a complicated nonlinear manner.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] When fully written out, the EFE are a system of ten coupled, nonlinear, hyperbolic-elliptic partial differential equations.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] The above form of the EFE is the standard established by Misner, Thorne, and Wheeler (MTW).
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] With these definitions Misner, Thorne, and Wheeler classify themselves as (+ + +), whereas Weinberg (1972) is (+ − −), Peebles (1980) and Efstathiou et al.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] The sign of the cosmological term would change in both these versions if the (+ − − −) metric sign convention is used rather than the MTW (− + + +) metric sign convention adopted here.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] Taking the trace with respect to the metric of both sides of the EFE one gets $R-{\frac {D}{2}}R+D\Lambda =\kappa T,$ where D is the spacetime dimension.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] Reversing the trace again would restore the original EFE.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] The trace-reversed form may be more convenient in some cases (for example, when one is interested in weak-field limit and can replace $g_{\mu \nu }$ in the expression on the right with the Minkowski metric without significant loss of accuracy).
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] In the Einstein field equations $G_{\mu \nu }+\Lambda g_{\mu \nu }=\kappa T_{\mu \nu }\,,$ the term containing the cosmological constant $\Lambda$ was absent from the version in which he originally published them.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] Einstein then included the term with the cosmological constant to allow for a universe that is not expanding or contracting.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] Einstein then abandoned $\Lambda$ , remarking to George Gamow "that the introduction of the cosmological term was the biggest blunder of his life".
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] The inclusion of this term does not create inconsistencies.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] For many years the cosmological constant was almost universally assumed to be zero.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] More recent astronomical observations have shown an accelerating expansion of the universe, and to explain this a positive value of $\Lambda$ is needed.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] The effect of the cosmological constant is negligible at the scale of a galaxy or smaller.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] The existence of a cosmological constant is thus equivalent to the existence of a vacuum energy and a pressure of opposite sign.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] This has led to the terms "cosmological constant" and "vacuum energy" being used interchangeably in general relativity.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] which expresses the local conservation of stress–energy.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] This conservation law is a physical requirement.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] With his field equations Einstein ensured that general relativity is consistent with this conservation condition.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] The nonlinearity of the EFE distinguishes general relativity from many other fundamental physical theories.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] For example, Maxwell's equations of electromagnetism are linear in the electric and magnetic fields, and charge and current distributions (i.e. the sum of two solutions is also a solution); another example is the Schrödinger equation of quantum mechanics, which is linear in the wavefunction.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] The EFE reduce to Newton's law of gravity by using both the weak-field approximation and the low-velocity approximation.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] The constant G appearing in the EFE is determined by making these two approximations.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] Applying these simplifying assumptions to the spatial components of the geodesic equation gives ${\frac {d^{2}x^{i}}{dt^{2}}}\approx -\Gamma _{00}^{i}$ where two factors of ${\textstyle {\frac {{\text{d}}t}{{\text{d}}\tau }}}$ have been divided out.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] Our assumptions force $\alpha =i$ and the time (0) derivatives to be zero.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] If the energy–momentum tensor $T_{\mu \nu }$ is zero in the region under consideration, then the field equations are also referred to as the vacuum field equations.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] The solutions to the vacuum field equations are called vacuum solutions.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] Flat Minkowski space is the simplest example of a vacuum solution.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] Nontrivial examples include the Schwarzschild solution and the Kerr solution.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] Manifolds with a vanishing Ricci tensor, $R_{\mu \nu }=0$ , are referred to as Ricci-flat manifolds and manifolds with a Ricci tensor proportional to the metric as Einstein manifolds.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] The first equation asserts that the 4-divergence of the 2-form F is zero, and the second that its exterior derivative is zero.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] This is often taken as equivalent to the covariant Maxwell equation from which it is derived.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] However, there are global solutions of the equation that may lack a globally defined potential.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] The solutions of the Einstein field equations are metrics of spacetime.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] These metrics describe the structure of the spacetime including the inertial motion of objects in the spacetime.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] As the field equations are non-linear, they cannot always be completely solved (i.e. without making approximations).
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] For example, there is no known complete solution for a spacetime with two massive bodies in it (which is a theoretical model of a binary star system, for example).
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] However, approximations are usually made in these cases.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] These are commonly referred to as post-Newtonian approximations.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] Even so, there are several cases where the field equations have been solved completely, and those are called exact solutions.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] The study of exact solutions of Einstein's field equations is one of the activities of cosmology.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] It leads to the prediction of black holes and to different models of evolution of the universe.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] One can also discover new solutions of the Einstein field equations via the method of orthonormal frames as pioneered by Ellis and MacCallum.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] In this approach, the Einstein field equations are reduced to a set of coupled, nonlinear, ordinary differential equations.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] As discussed by Hsu and Wainwright, self-similar solutions to the Einstein field equations are fixed points of the resulting dynamical system.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] New solutions have been discovered using these methods by LeBlanc and Kohli and Haslam.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] The nonlinearity of the EFE makes finding exact solutions difficult.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] One way of solving the field equations is to make an approximation, namely, that far from the source(s) of gravitating matter, the gravitational field is very weak and the spacetime approximates that of Minkowski space.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] The metric is then written as the sum of the Minkowski metric and a term representing the deviation of the true metric from the Minkowski metric, ignoring higher-power terms.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] This linearization procedure can be used to investigate the phenomena of gravitational radiation.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] Despite the EFE as written containing the inverse of the metric tensor, they can be arranged in a form that contains the metric tensor in polynomial form and without its inverse.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] Substituting this expression of the inverse of the metric into the equations then multiplying both sides by a suitable power of $\det(g)$ to eliminate it from the denominator results in polynomial equations in the metric tensor and its first and second derivatives.
[src:general-relativity/einstein-field-equations] The Einstein–Hilbert action from which the equations are derived can also be written in polynomial form by suitable redefinitions of the fields.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] The **equivalence principle** is the hypothesis that the observed equivalence of gravitational and inertial mass is a consequence of nature.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] The weak form, known for centuries, relates to masses of any composition in free fall taking the same trajectories and landing at identical times.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] The extended form by Albert Einstein requires special relativity to also hold in free fall and requires the weak equivalence to be valid everywhere.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] This form was a critical input for the development of the theory of general relativity.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] The strong form requires Einstein's form to work for stellar objects.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Highly precise experimental tests of the principle limit possible deviations from equivalence to be very small.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Careful experiments have shown that the inertial mass on the left side and gravitational mass on the right side are numerically equal and independent of the material composing the masses.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] The equivalence principle is the hypothesis that this numerical equality of inertial and gravitational mass is a consequence of their fundamental identity.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] The equivalence principle can be considered an extension of the principle of relativity, the principle that the laws of physics are invariant under uniform motion.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] An observer in a windowless room cannot distinguish between being in a uniform gravitational field of 1*g* and being in a spaceship in deep space accelerating at 1*g*.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Observations of physical phenomena in these cases will be indistinguishable.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] In Newton's law of gravity, the equivalence principle is viewed as an observation, an accident of nature encoded in empirical law.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] In Einstein's model of gravity, the equivalence principle is a consequence of physics.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] The same mass both causes and responds to gravity: mass causes spacetime curvature and then moves through spacetime according to that curvature.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] By experimenting with the acceleration of different materials, Galileo Galilei determined that gravitation is independent of the amount of mass being accelerated.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Isaac Newton, just 50 years after Galileo, investigated whether gravitational and inertial mass might be different concepts.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] He compared the periods of pendulums composed of different materials and found them to be identical.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] From this, he inferred that gravitational and inertial mass are the same thing.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] The form of this assertion, where the equivalence principle is taken to follow from empirical consistency, later became known as "weak equivalence".
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Since the physical laws are the same, Einstein assumed the gravitational field and the acceleration were "physically equivalent".
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] In 1911 Einstein demonstrated the power of the equivalence principle by using it to predict that clocks run at different rates in a gravitational potential, and light rays bend in a gravitational field.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Einstein's development of general relativity necessitated some means of empirically discriminating the theory from other theories of gravity compatible with special relativity.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Accordingly, Robert Dicke developed a test program incorporating two new principles – the § Einstein equivalence principle, and the § Strong equivalence principle – each of which assumes the weak equivalence principle as a starting point.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Three main forms of the equivalence principle are in current use: weak (Galilean), Einsteinian, and strong.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Some proposals also suggest finer divisions or minor alterations.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] The **weak equivalence principle**, also known as the **universality of free fall** or the **Galilean equivalence principle** assumes falling bodies are self-bound by non-gravitational forces only (e.g. a stone).
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] the outcome of any local, non-gravitational test experiment is independent of the experimental apparatus' velocity relative to the gravitational field and is independent of where and when in the gravitational field the experiment is performed.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Here *local* means that experimental setup must be small compared to variations in the gravitational field, called tidal forces.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] The *test* experiment must be small enough so that its gravitational potential does not alter the result.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] With these constraints alone Einstein was able to predict the gravitational redshift.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Theories of gravity that obey the Einstein equivalence principle must be "metric theories", meaning that trajectories of freely falling bodies are geodesics of symmetric metric.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Schiff conjectured that any complete and consistent theory of gravity that embodies the weak equivalence principle implies the Einstein equivalence principle; the conjecture can't be proven but has several plausibility arguments in its favor.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Nonetheless, the two principles are tested with very different kinds of experiments.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] The Einstein equivalence principle has been criticized as imprecise, because there is no universally accepted way to distinguish gravitational from non-gravitational experiments (see for instance Hadley and Durand).
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] The strong equivalence principle applies the same constraints as the Einstein equivalence principle, but allows the freely falling bodies to be massive gravitating objects as well as test particles.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] The strong equivalence principle includes astronomic bodies with gravitational self-binding energy.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Thus this is a version of the equivalence principle that applies to objects that exert a gravitational force on themselves, such as stars, planets, black holes or Cavendish experiments.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] It requires that the gravitational constant be the same everywhere in the universe.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] It is much more restrictive than the Einstein equivalence principle.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Like the Einstein equivalence principle, the strong equivalence principle requires gravity to be geometrical by nature, but in addition it forbids any extra fields, so the metric alone determines all of the effects of gravity.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] If an observer measures a patch of space to be flat, then the strong equivalence principle suggests that it is absolutely equivalent to any other patch of flat space elsewhere in the universe.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Einstein's theory of general relativity (including the cosmological constant) is thought to be the only theory of gravity that satisfies the strong equivalence principle.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] A number of alternative theories, such as Brans–Dicke theory and the Einstein-aether theory add additional fields.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Some of the tests of the equivalence principle use names for the different ways mass appears in physical formulae.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Passive mass, the response to gravity, the object's weight.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Active mass, the mass that determines the object's gravitational effect.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] In other words, passive gravitational mass must be proportional to inertial mass for objects, independent of their material composition if the weak equivalence principle is obeyed.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] A similar parameter can be used to compare passive and active mass.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] In words, passive gravitational mass must be proportional to active gravitational mass for all objects.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Tests of the weak equivalence principle are those that verify the equivalence of gravitational mass and inertial mass.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] An obvious test is dropping different objects and verifying that they land at the same time.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Historically this was the first approach – though probably not by Galileo's Leaning Tower of Pisa experiment but instead earlier by Simon Stevin, who dropped lead balls of different masses off the Delft churchtower and listened for the sound of them hitting a wooden plank.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Newton measured the period of pendulums made with different materials as an alternative test giving the first precision measurements.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Loránd Eötvös's approach in 1908 used a very sensitive torsion balance to give precision approaching 1 in a billion.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Modern experiments have improved this by another factor of a million.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] A popular exposition of this measurement was done on the Moon by David Scott in 1971.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] He dropped a falcon feather and a hammer at the same time, showing on video that they landed at the same time.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Experiments are still being performed at the University of Washington which have placed limits on the differential acceleration of objects towards the Earth, the Sun and towards dark matter in the Galactic Center.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Proposals for satellite experiments to test the weak equivalence principle in space to much higher accuracy include Satellite Test of the Equivalence Principle and GG (for Galileo Galilei).
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] With the first successful production of antimatter, in particular anti-hydrogen, a new approach to test the weak equivalence principle has been proposed.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Experiments to compare the gravitational behavior of matter and antimatter are currently being developed.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Heuristic arguments suggest that the magnitude of these equivalence principle violations could be in the 10−13 to 10−18 range.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Currently envisioned tests of the weak equivalence principle are approaching a degree of sensitivity such that *non-discovery* of a violation would be just as profound a result as discovery of a violation.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Non-discovery of equivalence principle violation in this range would suggest that gravity is so fundamentally different from other forces as to require a major reevaluation of current attempts to unify gravity with the other forces of nature.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] A positive detection, on the other hand, would provide a major guidepost towards unification.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] In addition to the tests of the weak equivalence principle, the Einstein equivalence principle requires testing the local Lorentz invariance and local positional invariance conditions.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Testing local Lorentz invariance amounts to testing special relativity, a theory with a vast number of existing tests.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Nevertheless, attempts to look for quantum gravity require even more precise tests.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] The modern tests include looking for directional variations in the speed of light (called "clock anisotropy tests") and new forms of the Michelson–Morley experiment.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] The anisotropy measures less than one part in 10−20.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Testing local positional invariance divides into tests in space and in time.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Space-based tests use measurements of the gravitational redshift, the classic is the Pound–Rebka experiment in the 1960s.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] The most precise measurement was done in 1976 by flying a hydrogen maser and comparing it to one on the ground.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] The Global Positioning System requires compensation for this redshift to give accurate position values.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Time-based tests search for variation of fundamental physical constants.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] For example, Webb et al. reported detection of variation (at the 10−5 level) of the fine-structure constant from measurements of distant quasars.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Other researchers dispute these findings.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] These reactions are extremely sensitive to the values of the fundamental constants.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Orbital variations due to gravitational self-energy should cause a "polarization" of solar system orbits called the Nordtvedt effect.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] This effect has been sensitively tested by Lunar Laser Ranging experiments.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Up to the limit of one part in 1013 there is no Nordtvedt effect.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] A tight bound on the effect of nearby gravitational fields on the strong equivalence principle comes from modeling the orbits of binary stars and comparing the results to pulsar timing data.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] In 2014, astronomers discovered a stellar triple system containing a millisecond pulsar PSR J0337+1715 and two white dwarfs orbiting it.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] The system provided them a chance to test the strong equivalence principle in a strong gravitational field with high accuracy.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] If there is any departure from the strong equivalence principle, it is no more than two parts per million.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Most alternative theories of gravity predict a change in the gravity constant over time.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Studies of Big Bang nucleosynthesis, analysis of pulsars, and the lunar laser ranging data have shown that *G* cannot have varied by more than 10% since the creation of the universe.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] The best data comes from studies of the ephemeris of Mars, based on three successive NASA missions, Mars Global Surveyor, Mars Odyssey, and Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Precisely phrased definitions of the equivalence principle exclude test bodies with electric charge.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] A charged and uncharged ball dropped in a gravitational field results in a paradox.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] To an observer standing where the balls will land, the accelerating charged ball will lose kinetic energy by emitting radiation and will hence reach the floor *after* the uncharged ball.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] To an observer falling with the balls, the radiation starts when the charged ball lands on the ground.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] This does not point to any defect in the equivalence principle itself, only to oversimplified statements of the principle.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] A charged particle together with its associated electromagnetic field cannot in general be treated as confined to an arbitrarily small neighborhood, since the field extends beyond the local region in which the equivalence principle applies.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] As the charged and neutral balls are released side by side, the balls will initially accelerate identically.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] But after a short period of time, the charged ball will experience a back reaction from its own electromagnetic fields.
[src:general-relativity/equivalence-principle] Quantitative treatment of electromagnetic self-force in curved spacetime is technically difficult.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Newton's law of universal gravitation, which describes gravity in classical mechanics, can be seen as a prediction of general relativity for the almost flat spacetime geometry around stationary mass distributions.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Some predictions of general relativity, however, are beyond Newton's law of universal gravitation in classical physics.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] These predictions concern the passage of time, the geometry of space, the motion of bodies in free fall, and the propagation of light, and include gravitational time dilation, gravitational lensing, the gravitational redshift of light, the Shapiro time delay, singularities and black holes.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] So far, all tests of general relativity have been in agreement with the theory.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] The time-dependent solutions of general relativity enable us to extrapolate the history of the universe into the past and future, and have provided the modern framework for cosmology, thus leading to the discovery of the Big Bang and cosmic microwave background radiation.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Despite the introduction of a number of alternative theories, general relativity continues to be the simplest theory consistent with experimental data.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Reconciliation of general relativity with the laws of quantum physics remains a problem, however, as no self-consistent theory of quantum gravity has been found.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] It is not yet known how gravity can be unified with the three non-gravitational interactions: strong, weak and electromagnetic.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Einstein's theory has astrophysical implications, including the prediction of black holes—regions of space in which space and time are distorted in such a way that nothing, not even light, can escape from them.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Black holes are the end-state for massive stars.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Microquasars and active galactic nuclei are believed to be stellar black holes and supermassive black holes.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] It also predicts gravitational lensing, where the bending of light results in distorted and multiple images of the same distant astronomical phenomenon.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Other predictions include the existence of gravitational waves, which have been observed directly by the physics collaboration LIGO and other observatories.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] In addition, general relativity has provided the basis for cosmological models of an expanding universe.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Widely acknowledged as a theory of extraordinary mathematical beauty, general relativity has often been described as the most beautiful of all existing physical theories.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Henri Poincaré's 1905 theory of the dynamics of the electron was a relativistic theory which he applied to all forces, including gravity.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] While others thought that gravity was instantaneous or of electromagnetic origin, he suggested that relativity was "something due to our methods of measurement".
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] In his theory, he proposed that gravitational waves propagate at the speed of light.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Soon afterwards, Einstein started thinking about how to incorporate gravity into his relativistic framework.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] In 1907, beginning with a simple thought experiment involving an observer in free fall (FFO), he embarked on what would be an eight-year search for a relativistic theory of gravity.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] After numerous detours and false starts, his work culminated in the presentation to the Prussian Academy of Science in November 1915 of what are known as the Einstein field equations, which form the core of Einstein's general theory of relativity.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] These equations specify how the geometry of space and time is influenced by whatever matter and radiation are present.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] A version of non-Euclidean geometry, called Riemannian geometry, enabled Einstein to develop general relativity by providing the key mathematical framework on which he fit his physical ideas of gravity.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] This idea was pointed out by mathematician Marcel Grossmann and published by Grossmann and Einstein in 1913.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] The Einstein field equations are nonlinear and are considered difficult to solve.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Einstein used approximation methods in working out initial predictions of the theory.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] But in 1916, the astrophysicist Karl Schwarzschild found the first non-trivial exact solution to the Einstein field equations, the Schwarzschild metric.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] This solution laid the groundwork for the description of the final stages of gravitational collapse, and the objects known today as black holes.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] In the same year, the first steps towards generalizing Schwarzschild's solution to electrically charged objects were taken, eventually resulting in the Reissner–Nordström solution, which is associated with electrically charged black holes.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] In 1917, Einstein applied his theory to the universe as a whole, initiating the field of relativistic cosmology.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] In line with contemporary thinking, he assumed a static universe, adding a new parameter to his original field equations—the cosmological constant—to match that observational presumption.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] By 1929, however, the work of Hubble and others had shown that the universe is expanding.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] This is readily described by the expanding cosmological solutions found by Friedmann in 1922, which do not require a cosmological constant.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Lemaître used these solutions to formulate the earliest version of the Big Bang models, in which the universe has evolved from an extremely hot and dense earlier state.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Einstein later declared the cosmological constant the biggest blunder of his life.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] During that period, general relativity remained something of a curiosity among physical theories.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] It was clearly superior to Newtonian gravity, being consistent with special relativity and accounting for several effects unexplained by the Newtonian theory.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Yet the theory remained outside the mainstream of theoretical physics and astrophysics until developments between approximately 1960 and 1975 known as the golden age of general relativity.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Physicists began to understand the concept of a black hole, and to identify quasars as one of these objects' astrophysical manifestations.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Ever more precise solar system tests confirmed the theory's predictive power, and relativistic cosmology also became amenable to direct observational tests.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] General relativity has acquired a reputation as a theory of extraordinary beauty.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Subrahmanyan Chandrasekhar has noted that at multiple levels, general relativity exhibits what Francis Bacon has termed a "strangeness in the proportion" (*i.e.* elements that excite wonderment and surprise).
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] It juxtaposes fundamental concepts (space and time *versus* matter and motion) which had previously been considered as entirely independent.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Other elements of beauty associated with the general theory of relativity are its simplicity and symmetry, the manner in which it incorporates invariance and unification, and its perfect logical consistency.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] The work presumes a standard of education corresponding to that of a university matriculation examination, and, despite the shortness of the book, a fair amount of patience and force of will on the part of the reader.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] General relativity can be understood by examining its similarities with and departures from classical physics.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] The first step is the realization that classical mechanics and Newton's law of gravity admit a geometric description.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] The combination of this description with the laws of special relativity results in a heuristic derivation of general relativity.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] At the base of classical mechanics is the notion that a body's motion can be described as a combination of free (or inertial) motion, and deviations from this free motion.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Such deviations are caused by external forces acting on a body in accordance with Newton's second law of motion, which states that the net force acting on a body is equal to that body's (inertial) mass multiplied by its acceleration.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] The preferred inertial motions are related to the geometry of space and time: in the standard reference frames of classical mechanics, objects in free motion move along straight lines at constant speed.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] In modern parlance, their paths are geodesics, straight world lines in curved spacetime.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Conversely, one might expect that inertial motions, once identified by observing the actual motions of bodies and making allowances for the external forces (such as electromagnetism or friction), can be used to define the geometry of space, as well as a time coordinate.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] However, there is an ambiguity once gravity comes into play.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Given the universality of free fall, there is no observable distinction between inertial motion and motion under the influence of the gravitational force.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] This suggests the definition of a new class of inertial motion, namely that of objects in free fall under the influence of gravity.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] This new class of preferred motions, too, defines a geometry of space and time—in mathematical terms, it is the geodesic motion associated with a specific connection which depends on the gradient of the gravitational potential.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Space, in this construction, still has the ordinary Euclidean geometry.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] However, space*time* as a whole is more complicated.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] From this, one can deduce that spacetime is curved.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] The resulting Newton–Cartan theory is a geometric formulation of Newtonian gravity using only covariant concepts, i.e. a description which is valid in any desired coordinate system.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] In this geometric description, tidal effects—the relative acceleration of bodies in free fall—are related to the derivative of the connection, showing how the modified geometry is caused by the presence of mass.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] As intriguing as geometric Newtonian gravity may be, its basis, classical mechanics, is merely a limiting case of (special) relativistic mechanics.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] In the language of symmetry: where gravity can be neglected, physics is Lorentz invariant as in special relativity rather than Galilei invariant as in classical mechanics.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] (The defining symmetry of special relativity is the Poincaré group, which includes translations, rotations, boosts and reflections.) The differences between the two become significant when dealing with speeds approaching the speed of light, and with high-energy phenomena.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] With Lorentz symmetry, additional structures come into play.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] They are defined by the set of light cones (see image).
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] In conjunction with the world-lines of freely falling particles, the light-cones can be used to reconstruct the spacetime's semi-Riemannian metric, at least up to a positive scalar factor.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] In mathematical terms, this defines a conformal structure or conformal geometry.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Special relativity is defined in the absence of gravity.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] For practical applications, it is a suitable model whenever gravity can be neglected.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Bringing gravity into play, and assuming the universality of free fall motion, an analogous reasoning as in the previous section applies: there are no global inertial frames.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Instead there are approximate inertial frames moving alongside freely falling particles.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Translated into the language of spacetime: the straight time-like lines that define a gravity-free inertial frame are deformed to lines that are curved relative to each other, suggesting that the inclusion of gravity necessitates a change in spacetime geometry.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] A priori, it is not clear whether the new local frames in free fall coincide with the reference frames in which the laws of special relativity hold—that theory is based on the propagation of light, and thus on electromagnetism, which could have a different set of preferred frames.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] The actual measurements show that free-falling frames are the ones in which light propagates as it does in special relativity.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] The same experimental data shows that time as measured by clocks in a gravitational field—proper time, to give the technical term—does not follow the rules of special relativity.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] In the language of spacetime geometry, it is not measured by the Minkowski metric.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] As in the Newtonian case, this is suggestive of a more general geometry.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] At small scales, all reference frames that are in free fall are equivalent, and approximately Minkowskian.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Consequently, we are dealing with a curved generalization of Minkowski space.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] The metric tensor that defines the geometry—in particular, how lengths and angles are measured—is not the Minkowski metric of special relativity, it is a generalization known as a semi- or pseudo-Riemannian metric.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Having formulated the relativistic, geometric version of the effects of gravity, the question of gravity's source remains.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] In Newtonian gravity, the source is mass.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] In special relativity, mass turns out to be part of a more general quantity called the stress–energy tensor, which includes both energy and momentum densities as well as stress: pressure and shear.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Using the equivalence principle, this tensor is readily generalized to curved spacetime.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] In special relativity, conservation of energy–momentum corresponds to the statement that the stress–energy tensor is divergence-free.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] This formula, too, is readily generalized to curved spacetime by replacing partial derivatives with their curved-manifold counterparts, covariant derivatives studied in differential geometry.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] On the left-hand side is the Einstein tensor, $G_{\mu \nu }$ , which is symmetric and a specific divergence-free combination of the Ricci tensor $R_{\mu \nu }$ and the metric.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] In particular, $R=g^{\mu \nu }R_{\mu \nu }$ is the curvature scalar.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] On the right-hand side, $\kappa$ is a constant and $T_{\mu \nu }$ is the stress–energy tensor.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] All tensors are written in abstract index notation.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] In general relativity, the world line of a particle free from all external, non-gravitational force is a particular type of geodesic in curved spacetime.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] In other words, a freely moving or falling particle always moves along a geodesic.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Greek indices may take the values: 0, 1, 2, 3 and the summation convention is used for repeated indices $\alpha$ and $\beta$ .
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] The quantity on the left-hand-side of this equation is the acceleration of a particle, and so this equation is analogous to Newton's laws of motion which likewise provide formulae for the acceleration of a particle.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] This equation of motion employs the Einstein notation, meaning that repeated indices are summed (i.e. from zero to three).
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] The Christoffel symbols are functions of the four spacetime coordinates, and so are independent of the velocity or acceleration or other characteristics of a test particle whose motion is described by the geodesic equation.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] The first term represents the force of Newtonian gravity, which is described by the inverse-square law.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] The second term represents the centrifugal force in the circular motion.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] The third term represents the relativistic effect.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] There are alternatives to general relativity built upon the same premises, which include additional rules and/or constraints, leading to different field equations.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Examples are Whitehead's theory, Brans–Dicke theory, teleparallelism, *f*(*R*) gravity and Einstein–Cartan theory.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] The derivation outlined in the previous section contains all the information needed to define general relativity, describe its key properties, and address a question of crucial importance in physics, namely how the theory can be used for model-building.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] General relativity is a metric theory of gravitation.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] At its core are Einstein's equations, which describe the relation between the geometry of a four-dimensional pseudo-Riemannian manifold representing spacetime, and the distribution of energy, momentum and stress contained in that spacetime.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Instead, gravity corresponds to changes in the properties of space and time, which in turn changes the straightest-possible paths that objects will naturally follow.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] The curvature is, in turn, caused by the stress–energy of matter.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Paraphrasing the relativist John Archibald Wheeler, spacetime tells matter how to move; matter tells spacetime how to curve.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] While general relativity replaces the scalar gravitational potential of classical physics by a symmetric rank-two tensor, the latter reduces to the former in certain limiting cases.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] For weak gravitational fields and low speed relative to the speed of light, the theory's predictions converge on those of Newton's law of universal gravitation.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] As it is constructed using tensors, general relativity exhibits general covariance: its laws—and further laws formulated within the general relativistic framework—take on the same form in all coordinate systems.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Furthermore, the theory does not contain any invariant geometric background structures, i.e. it is background-independent.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] It thus satisfies a more stringent general principle of relativity, namely that the laws of physics are the same for all observers.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Locally, as expressed in the equivalence principle, spacetime is Minkowskian, and the laws of physics exhibit local Lorentz invariance.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] The core concept of general-relativistic model-building is that of a solution of Einstein's equations.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Given both Einstein's equations and suitable equations for the properties of matter, such a solution consists of a specific semi-Riemannian manifold (usually defined by giving the metric in specific coordinates), and specific matter fields defined on that manifold.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Matter and geometry must satisfy Einstein's equations, so in particular, the matter's stress–energy tensor must be divergence-free.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] The matter must, of course, also satisfy whatever additional equations were imposed on its properties.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] In short, such a solution is a model universe that satisfies the laws of general relativity, and possibly additional laws governing whatever matter might be present.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Einstein's equations are nonlinear partial differential equations and, as such, difficult to solve exactly.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Nevertheless, a number of exact solutions are known, although only a few have direct physical applications.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Given the difficulty of finding exact solutions, Einstein's field equations are also solved frequently by numerical integration on a computer, or by considering small perturbations of exact solutions.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] In the field of numerical relativity, powerful computers are employed to simulate the geometry of spacetime and to solve Einstein's equations for interesting situations such as two colliding black holes.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] In principle, such methods may be applied to any system, given sufficient computer resources, and may address fundamental questions such as naked singularities.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Approximate solutions may also be found by perturbation theories such as linearized gravity and its generalization, the post-Newtonian expansion, both of which were developed by Einstein.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] The latter provides a systematic approach to solving for the geometry of a spacetime that contains a distribution of matter that moves slowly compared with the speed of light.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] The expansion involves a series of terms; the first terms represent Newtonian gravity, whereas the later terms represent ever smaller corrections to Newton's theory due to general relativity.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] An extension of this expansion is the parametrized post-Newtonian (PPN) formalism, which allows quantitative comparisons between the predictions of general relativity and alternative theories.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] General relativity has a number of physical consequences.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Some follow directly from the theory's axioms, whereas others have become clear only in the course of many years of research that followed Einstein's initial publication.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Assuming that the equivalence principle holds, gravity influences the passage of time.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Light sent down into a gravity well is blueshifted, whereas light sent in the opposite direction (i.e., climbing out of the gravity well) is redshifted; collectively, these two effects are known as the gravitational frequency shift.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] More generally, processes close to a massive body run more slowly when compared with processes taking place farther away; this effect is known as gravitational time dilation.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Gravitational redshift has been measured in the laboratory and using astronomical observations.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Gravitational time dilation in the Earth's gravitational field has been measured numerous times using atomic clocks, while ongoing validation is provided as a side effect of the operation of the Global Positioning System (GPS).
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Tests in stronger gravitational fields are provided by the observation of binary pulsars.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] All results are in agreement with general relativity.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] However, at the existing level of accuracy, these observations cannot distinguish between general relativity and other theories in which the equivalence principle is valid.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] General relativity predicts that the path of light will follow the curvature of spacetime as it passes near a massive object.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] This effect was initially confirmed by observing the light of stars or distant quasars being deflected as it passes the Sun.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] This and related predictions follow from the fact that light follows what is called a light-like or null geodesic—a generalization of the straight lines along which light travels in classical physics.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Such geodesics are the generalization of the invariance of lightspeed in special relativity.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] As one examines suitable model spacetimes (either the exterior Schwarzschild solution or, for more than a single mass, the post-Newtonian expansion), several effects of gravity on light propagation emerge.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Although the bending of light can also be derived by extending the universality of free fall to light, the angle of deflection resulting from such calculations is only half the value given by general relativity.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Closely related to light deflection is the Shapiro time delay, the phenomenon that light signals take longer to move through a gravitational field than they would in the absence of that field.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] There have been numerous successful tests of this prediction.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] In the parameterized post-Newtonian formalism (PPN), measurements of both the deflection of light and the gravitational time delay determine a parameter called *γ*, which encodes the influence of gravity on the geometry of space.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Predicted in 1916 by Albert Einstein, there are gravitational waves: ripples in the metric of spacetime that propagate at the speed of light.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] These are one of several analogies between weak-field gravity and electromagnetism in that, they are analogous to electromagnetic waves.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] On 11 February 2016, the Advanced LIGO team announced that they had directly detected gravitational waves from a pair of black holes merging.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] The simplest type of such a wave can be visualized by its action on a ring of freely floating particles.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] A sine wave propagating through such a ring towards the reader distorts the ring in a characteristic, rhythmic fashion (animated image to the right).
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Since Einstein's equations are non-linear, arbitrarily strong gravitational waves do not obey linear superposition, making their description difficult.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] However, linear approximations of gravitational waves are sufficiently accurate to describe the exceedingly weak waves that are expected to arrive here on Earth from far-off cosmic events, which typically result in relative distances increasing and decreasing by 10−21 or less.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Data analysis methods routinely make use of the fact that these linearized waves can be Fourier decomposed.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Some exact solutions describe gravitational waves without any approximation, e.g., a wave train traveling through empty space or Gowdy universes, varieties of an expanding cosmos filled with gravitational waves.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] But for gravitational waves produced in astrophysically relevant situations, such as the merger of two black holes, numerical methods are the only way to construct appropriate models.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] General relativity differs from classical mechanics in a number of predictions concerning orbiting bodies.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] It predicts an overall rotation (precession) of planetary orbits, as well as orbital decay caused by the emission of gravitational waves and effects related to the relativity of direction.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] In general relativity, the apsides of any orbit (the point of the orbiting body's closest approach to the system's center of mass) will precess; the orbit is not an ellipse, but akin to an ellipse that rotates on its focus, resulting in a rose curve-like shape (see image).
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Einstein first derived this result by using an approximate metric representing the Newtonian limit and treating the orbiting body as a test particle.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] For him, the fact that his theory gave a straightforward explanation of Mercury's anomalous perihelion shift, discovered earlier by Urbain Le Verrier in 1859, was important evidence that he had at last identified the correct form of the gravitational field equations.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] The effect can also be derived by using either the exact Schwarzschild metric (describing spacetime around a spherical mass) or the much more general post-Newtonian formalism.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] It is due to the influence of gravity on the geometry of space and to the contribution of self-energy to a body's gravity (encoded in the nonlinearity of Einstein's equations).
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Relativistic precession has been observed for all planets that allow for accurate precession measurements (Mercury, Venus, and Earth), as well as in binary pulsar systems, where it is larger by five orders of magnitude.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] According to general relativity, a binary system will emit gravitational waves, thereby losing energy.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Due to this loss, the distance between the two orbiting bodies decreases, and so does their orbital period.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Within the Solar System or for ordinary double stars, the effect is too small to be observable.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] This is not the case for a close binary pulsar, a system of two orbiting neutron stars, one of which is a pulsar: from the pulsar, observers on Earth receive a regular series of radio pulses that can serve as a highly accurate clock, which allows precise measurements of the orbital period.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Because neutron stars are immensely compact, significant amounts of energy are emitted in the form of gravitational radiation.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] The first observation of a decrease in orbital period due to the emission of gravitational waves was made by Hulse and Taylor, using the binary pulsar PSR1913+16 they had discovered in 1974.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] This was the first detection of gravitational waves, albeit indirect, for which they were awarded the 1993 Nobel Prize in physics.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Since then, several other binary pulsars have been found, in particular the double pulsar PSR J0737−3039, where both stars are pulsars and which was last reported to also be in agreement with general relativity in 2021 after 16 years of observations.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Several relativistic effects are directly related to the relativity of direction.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] For the Moon–Earth system, this effect has been measured with the help of lunar laser ranging.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] More recently, it has been measured for test masses aboard the satellite Gravity Probe B to a precision of better than 0.3%.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Near a rotating mass, there are gravitomagnetic or frame-dragging effects.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] A distant observer will determine that objects close to the mass get "dragged around".
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] This is most extreme for rotating black holes where, for any object entering a zone known as the ergosphere, rotation is inevitable.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Such effects can again be tested through their influence on the orientation of gyroscopes in free fall.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Somewhat controversial tests have been performed using the LAGEOS satellites, confirming the relativistic prediction.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Also the Mars Global Surveyor probe around Mars has been used.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] The deflection of light by gravity is responsible for a new class of astronomical phenomena.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] If a massive object is situated between the astronomer and a distant target object with appropriate mass and relative distances, the astronomer will see multiple distorted images of the target.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Such effects are known as gravitational lensing.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Depending on the configuration, scale, and mass distribution, there can be two or more images, a bright ring known as an Einstein ring, or partial rings called arcs.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] The earliest example was discovered in 1979; since then, more than a hundred gravitational lenses have been observed.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Even if the multiple images are too close to each other to be resolved, the effect can still be measured, e.g., as an overall brightening of the target object; a number of such "microlensing events" have been observed.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Gravitational lensing has developed into a tool of observational astronomy.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] It is used to detect the presence and distribution of dark matter, provide a "natural telescope" for observing distant galaxies, and to obtain an independent estimate of the Hubble constant.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Statistical evaluations of lensing data provide valuable insight into the structural evolution of galaxies.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Observations of binary pulsars provide strong indirect evidence for the existence of gravitational waves (see Orbital decay, above).
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Detection of these waves is a major goal of contemporary relativity-related research.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Several land-based gravitational wave detectors are in operation, for example the interferometric detectors GEO 600, LIGO (two detectors), TAMA 300 and VIRGO.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Various pulsar timing arrays are using millisecond pulsars to detect gravitational waves in the 10−9 to 10−6 hertz frequency range, which originate from binary supermassive black holes.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] A European space-based detector, eLISA / NGO, is under development, with a precursor mission (LISA Pathfinder) having launched in December 2015.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Observations of gravitational waves promise to complement observations in the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] They are expected to yield information about black holes and other dense objects such as neutron stars and white dwarfs, about certain kinds of supernova implosions, and about processes in the very early universe, including the signature of certain types of hypothetical cosmic string.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] In February 2016, the Advanced LIGO team announced that they had detected gravitational waves from a black hole merger.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Whenever the ratio of an object's mass to its radius becomes sufficiently large, general relativity predicts the formation of a black hole, a region of space from which nothing, not even light, can escape.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] In the accepted models of stellar evolution, neutron stars of around 1.4 solar masses, and stellar black holes with a few to a few dozen solar masses, are thought to be the final state for the evolution of massive stars.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Usually a galaxy has one supermassive black hole with a few million to a few billion solar masses in its center, and its presence is thought to have played an important role in the formation of the galaxy and larger cosmic structures.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Astronomically, the most important property of compact objects is that they provide a supremely efficient mechanism for converting gravitational energy into electromagnetic radiation.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Accretion, the falling of dust or gaseous matter onto stellar or supermassive black holes, is thought to be responsible for some spectacularly luminous astronomical objects, especially diverse kinds of active galactic nuclei on galactic scales and stellar-size objects such as microquasars.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] In particular, accretion can lead to relativistic jets, focused beams of highly energetic particles that are being flung into space at almost light speed.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] General relativity plays a central role in modelling all these phenomena, and observations provide strong evidence for the existence of black holes with the properties predicted by the theory.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Black holes are also sought-after targets in the search for gravitational waves (cf. section § Gravitational waves, above).
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] The gravitational waves produced as a stellar black hole plunges into a supermassive one should provide direct information about the supermassive black hole's geometry.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Isotropic and homogeneous solutions of these enhanced equations, the Friedmann–Lemaître–Robertson–Walker solutions, allow physicists to model a universe that has evolved over the past 14 billion years from a hot, early Big Bang phase.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Once a small number of parameters (for example the universe's mean matter density) have been fixed by astronomical observation, further observational data can be used to put the models to the test.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Predictions, all successful, include the initial abundance of chemical elements formed in a period of primordial nucleosynthesis, the large-scale structure of the universe, and the existence and properties of a "thermal echo" from the early cosmos, the cosmic background radiation.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Astronomical observations of the cosmological expansion rate allow the total amount of matter in the universe to be estimated, although the nature of that matter remains mysterious in part.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] About 90% of all matter appears to be dark matter, which has mass (or, equivalently, gravitational influence), but does not interact electromagnetically and, hence, cannot be observed directly.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] There is no generally accepted description of this new kind of matter, within the framework of known particle physics or otherwise.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Recent measurements of the cosmic background radiation have resulted in the first evidence for this scenario.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] However, there are a bewildering variety of possible inflationary scenarios, which cannot be restricted by existing observations.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] An even larger question is the physics of the earliest universe, prior to the inflationary phase and close to where the classical models predict the big bang singularity.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] An authoritative answer would require a complete theory of quantum gravity, which has not yet been developed (cf. the section on quantum gravity, below).
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Kurt Gödel showed that solutions to Einstein's equations exist that contain closed timelike curves (CTCs), which allow for loops in time.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] The solutions require extreme physical conditions unlikely ever to occur in practice, and it remains an open question whether further laws of physics will eliminate them completely.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Since then, other—similarly impractical—GR solutions containing CTCs have been found, such as the Tipler cylinder and traversable wormholes.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Stephen Hawking introduced chronology protection conjecture, which is an assumption beyond those of standard general relativity to prevent time travel.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p01] Some exact solutions in general relativity such as Alcubierre drive offer examples of warp drive but these solutions require exotic matter distribution, and generally suffer from semiclassical instability.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] The spacetime symmetry group for special relativity is the Poincaré group, which is a ten-dimensional group of three Lorentz boosts, three rotations, and four spacetime translations.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] It is logical to ask what symmetries, if any, might apply in General Relativity.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] A tractable case might be to consider the symmetries of spacetime as seen by observers located far away from all sources of the gravitational field.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] The naive expectation for asymptotically flat spacetime symmetries might be simply to extend and reproduce the symmetries of flat spacetime of special relativity, *viz.*, the Poincaré group.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Sachs addressed this asymptotic symmetry problem in order to investigate the flow of energy at infinity due to propagating gravitational waves.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Then after designing what they considered to be the most sensible boundary conditions, they investigated the nature of the resulting asymptotic symmetry transformations that leave invariant the form of the boundary conditions appropriate for asymptotically flat gravitational fields.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] What they found was that the asymptotic symmetry transformations actually do form a group and the structure of this group does not depend on the particular gravitational field that happens to be present.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] This means that, as expected, one can separate the kinematics of spacetime from the dynamics of the gravitational field at least at spatial infinity.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] The puzzling surprise in 1962 was their discovery of a rich infinite-dimensional group (the so-called BMS group) as the asymptotic symmetry group, instead of the finite-dimensional Poincaré group, which is a subgroup of the BMS group.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Not only are the Lorentz transformations asymptotic symmetry transformations, there are also additional transformations that are not Lorentz transformations but are asymptotic symmetry transformations.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] In fact, they found an additional infinity of transformation generators known as *supertranslations*.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] This implies the conclusion that General Relativity (GR) does *not* reduce to special relativity in the case of weak fields at long distances.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] It turns out that the BMS symmetry, suitably modified, could be seen as a restatement of the universal soft graviton theorem in quantum field theory (QFT), which relates universal infrared (soft) QFT with GR asymptotic spacetime symmetries.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] In general relativity, no material body can catch up with or overtake a light pulse.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] No influence from an event *A* can reach any other location *X* before light sent out at *A* to *X*.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] In consequence, an exploration of all light worldlines (null geodesics) yields key information about the spacetime's causal structure.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] This structure can be displayed using Penrose–Carter diagrams in which infinitely large regions of space and infinite time intervals are shrunk ("compactified") so as to fit onto a finite map, while light still travels along diagonals as in standard spacetime diagrams.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Aware of the importance of causal structure, Roger Penrose and others developed what is known as global geometry.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] In global geometry, the object of study is not one particular solution (or family of solutions) to Einstein's equations.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Rather, relations that hold true for all geodesics, such as the Raychaudhuri equation, and additional non-specific assumptions about the nature of matter (usually in the form of energy conditions) are used to derive general results.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Using global geometry, some spacetimes can be shown to contain boundaries called horizons, which demarcate one region from the rest of spacetime.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Since no object can overtake a light pulse, all interior matter is imprisoned as well.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Passage from the exterior to the interior is still possible, showing that the boundary, the black hole's *horizon*, is not a physical barrier.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Using global geometry, later studies have revealed more general properties of black holes.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] With time they become rather simple objects characterized by eleven parameters specifying: electric charge, mass–energy, linear momentum, angular momentum, and location at a specified time.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] This is stated by the black hole uniqueness theorem: "black holes have no hair", that is, no distinguishing marks like the hairstyles of humans.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Irrespective of the complexity of a gravitating object collapsing to form a black hole, the object that results (having emitted gravitational waves) is very simple.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Even more remarkably, there is a general set of laws known as black hole mechanics, which is analogous to the laws of thermodynamics.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] For instance, by the second law of black hole mechanics, the area of the event horizon of a general black hole will never decrease with time, analogous to the entropy of a thermodynamic system.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] This limits the energy that can be extracted by classical means from a rotating black hole (e.g. by the Penrose process).
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] There is strong evidence that the laws of black hole mechanics are, in fact, a subset of the laws of thermodynamics, and that the black hole area is proportional to its entropy.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] This leads to a modification of the original laws of black hole mechanics: for instance, as the second law of black hole mechanics becomes part of the second law of thermodynamics, it is possible for the black hole area to decrease as long as other processes ensure that entropy increases overall.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] As thermodynamical objects with nonzero temperature, black holes should emit thermal radiation.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Semiclassical calculations indicate that indeed they do, with the surface gravity playing the role of temperature in Planck's law.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] This radiation is known as Hawking radiation (cf. the quantum theory section, below).
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] In an expanding universe, an observer may find that some regions of the past cannot be observed ("particle horizon"), and some regions of the future cannot be influenced (event horizon).
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Even in flat Minkowski space, when described by an accelerated observer (Rindler space), there will be horizons associated with a semiclassical radiation known as Unruh radiation.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Another general feature of general relativity is the appearance of spacetime boundaries known as singularities.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Spacetime can be explored by following up on timelike and lightlike geodesics—all possible ways that light and particles in free fall can travel.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] But some solutions of Einstein's equations have "ragged edges"—regions known as spacetime singularities, where the paths of light and falling particles come to an abrupt end, and geometry becomes ill-defined.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] In the more interesting cases, these are "curvature singularities", where geometrical quantities characterizing spacetime curvature, such as the Ricci scalar, take on infinite values.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Well-known examples of spacetimes with future singularities—where worldlines end—are the Schwarzschild solution, which describes a singularity inside an eternal static black hole, or the Kerr solution with its ring-shaped singularity inside an eternal rotating black hole.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] The Friedmann–Lemaître–Robertson–Walker solutions and other spacetimes describing universes have past singularities on which worldlines begin, namely Big Bang singularities, and some have future singularities (Big Crunch) as well.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Given that these examples are all highly symmetric—and thus simplified—it is tempting to conclude that the occurrence of singularities is an artifact of idealization.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] However, the theorems say little about the properties of singularities, and much of current research is devoted to characterizing these entities' generic structure (hypothesized e.g. by the BKL conjecture).
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] The cosmic censorship hypothesis states that all realistic future singularities (no perfect symmetries, matter with realistic properties) are safely hidden away behind a horizon, and thus invisible to all distant observers.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] While no formal proof yet exists, numerical simulations offer supporting evidence of its validity.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Each solution of Einstein's equation encompasses the whole history of a universe—it is not just some snapshot of how things are, but a whole, possibly matter-filled, spacetime.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] It describes the state of matter and geometry everywhere and at every moment in that particular universe.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Due to its general covariance, Einstein's theory is not sufficient by itself to determine the time evolution of the metric tensor.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] It must be combined with a coordinate condition, which is analogous to gauge fixing in other field theories.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] To understand Einstein's equations as partial differential equations, it is helpful to formulate them in a way that describes the evolution of the universe over time.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] This is done in "3+1" formulations, where spacetime is split into three space dimensions and one time dimension.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] The best-known example is the ADM formalism.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] These decompositions show that the spacetime evolution equations of general relativity are well-behaved: solutions always exist, and are uniquely defined, once suitable initial conditions have been specified.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Such formulations of Einstein's field equations are the basis of numerical relativity.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] The notion of evolution equations is intimately tied in with another aspect of general relativistic physics.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] In Einstein's theory, it turns out to be impossible to find a general definition for a seemingly simple property such as a system's total mass (or energy).
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] The main reason is that the gravitational field—like any physical field—must be ascribed a certain energy, but that it proves to be fundamentally impossible to localize that energy.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Nevertheless, there are possibilities to define a system's total mass, either using a hypothetical "infinitely distant observer" (ADM mass) or suitable symmetries (Komar mass).
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] If one excludes from the system's total mass the energy being carried away to infinity by gravitational waves, the result is the Bondi mass at null infinity.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Just as in classical physics, it can be shown that these masses are positive.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Corresponding global definitions exist for momentum and angular momentum.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] There have also been a number of attempts to define *quasi-local* quantities, such as the mass of an isolated system formulated using only quantities defined within a finite region of space containing that system.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] The hope is to obtain a quantity useful for general statements about isolated systems, such as a more precise formulation of the hoop conjecture.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] If general relativity were considered to be one of the two pillars of modern physics, then quantum theory, the basis of understanding matter from elementary particles to solid-state physics, would be the other.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] However, how to reconcile quantum theory with general relativity is still an open question.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Ordinary quantum field theories, which form the basis of modern elementary particle physics, are defined in flat Minkowski space, which is an excellent approximation when it comes to describing the behavior of microscopic particles in weak gravitational fields like those found on Earth.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] In order to describe situations in which gravity is strong enough to influence (quantum) matter, yet not strong enough to require quantization itself, physicists have formulated quantum field theories in curved spacetime.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] These theories rely on general relativity to describe a curved background spacetime, and define a generalized quantum field theory to describe the behavior of quantum matter within that spacetime.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Using this formalism, it can be shown that black holes emit a blackbody spectrum of particles known as Hawking radiation leading to the possibility that they evaporate over time.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] As briefly mentioned above, this radiation plays an important role for the thermodynamics of black holes.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Despite major efforts, no complete and consistent theory of quantum gravity is currently known, even though a number of candidates exist.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Attempts to generalize ordinary quantum field theories, used in elementary particle physics to describe fundamental interactions, so as to include gravity have led to serious problems.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Some have argued that at low energies, this approach proves successful, in that it results in an acceptable effective (quantum) field theory of gravity.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] At very high energies, however, the perturbative results are badly divergent and lead to models devoid of predictive power ("perturbative non-renormalizability").
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] One attempt to overcome these limitations is string theory, a quantum theory not of point particles, but of minute one-dimensional extended objects.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] The theory promises to be a unified description of all particles and interactions, including gravity; the price to pay is unusual features such as six extra dimensions of space in addition to the usual three.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Another approach starts with the canonical quantization procedures of quantum theory.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Using the initial-value-formulation of general relativity (cf. evolution equations above), the result is the Wheeler–deWitt equation (an analogue of the Schrödinger equation) which turns out to be ill-defined without a proper ultraviolet (lattice) cutoff.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] However, with the introduction of what are now known as Ashtekar variables, this leads to a model known as loop quantum gravity.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Space is represented by a web-like structure called a spin network, evolving over time in discrete steps.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] All candidate theories still have major formal and conceptual problems to overcome.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] General relativity has emerged as a highly successful model of gravitation and cosmology, which has so far unambiguously fitted observational and experimental data.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] However, there are strong theoretical reasons to consider the theory to be incomplete.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] The problem of quantum gravity and the question of the reality of spacetime singularities remain open.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Observational data that is taken as evidence for dark energy and dark matter could also indicate the need to consider alternatives or modifications of general relativity.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Even taken as is, general relativity provides many possibilities for further exploration.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] Mathematical relativists seek to understand the nature of singularities and the fundamental properties of Einstein's equations, while numerical relativists run increasingly powerful computer simulations, such as those describing merging black holes.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] In February 2016, it was announced that gravitational waves were directly detected by the Advanced LIGO team on 14 September 2015.
[src:general-relativity/general-relativity-p02] A century after its introduction, general relativity remains a highly active area of research.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] In geometry, a **geodesic** (/ˌdʒiː.əˈdɛsɪk, -oʊ-, -ˈdiːsɪk, -zɪk/) is a curve representing in some sense the locally shortest path (arc) between two points in a surface, or more generally in a Riemannian manifold.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] The term also has meaning in any differentiable manifold with a connection.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] It is a generalization of the notion of a "straight line".
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] The noun *geodesic* and the adjective *geodetic* come from *geodesy*, the science of measuring the size and shape of Earth, though many of the underlying principles can be applied to any ellipsoidal geometry.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] In the original sense, a geodesic was the shortest route between two points on the Earth's surface.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] For a spherical Earth, it is a segment of a great circle (see also great-circle distance).
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] The term has since been generalized to more abstract mathematical spaces; for example, in graph theory, one might consider a geodesic between two vertices/nodes of a graph.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] In a Riemannian manifold or submanifold, geodesics are characterised by the property of having vanishing geodesic curvature.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] More generally, in the presence of an affine connection, a geodesic is defined to be a curve whose tangent vectors remain parallel if they are transported along it.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] Applying this to the Levi-Civita connection of a Riemannian metric recovers the previous notion.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] Geodesics are of particular importance in general relativity.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] Timelike geodesics in general relativity describe the motion of free falling test particles.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] This has some minor technical problems because there is an infinite-dimensional space of different ways to parameterize the shortest path.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] It is simpler to restrict the set of curves to those that are parameterized "with constant speed" 1, meaning that the distance from *f*(*s*) to *f*(*t*) along the curve equals |*s*−*t*|.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] Equivalently, a different quantity may be used, termed the energy of the curve; minimizing the energy leads to the same equations for a geodesic (here "constant velocity" is a consequence of minimization).
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] Intuitively, one can understand this second formulation by noting that an elastic band stretched between two points will contract its width, and in so doing will minimize its energy.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] The resulting shape of the band is a geodesic.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] It is possible that several different curves between two points minimize the distance, as is the case for two diametrically opposite points on a sphere.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] In such a case, any of these curves is a geodesic.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] A contiguous segment of a geodesic is again a geodesic.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] In general, geodesics are not the same as "shortest curves" between two points, though the two concepts are closely related.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] The difference is that geodesics are only *locally* the shortest distance between points, and are parameterized with "constant speed".
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] Going the "long way round" on a great circle between two points on a sphere is a geodesic but not the shortest path between the points.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] The map $t\to t^{2}$ from the unit interval on the real number line to itself gives the shortest path between 0 and 1, but is not a geodesic because the velocity of the corresponding motion of a point is not constant.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] Geodesics are commonly seen in the study of Riemannian geometry and more generally metric geometry.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] In general relativity, geodesics in spacetime describe the motion of point particles under the influence of gravity alone.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] In particular, the path taken by a falling rock, an orbiting satellite, or the shape of a planetary orbit are all geodesics in curved spacetime.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] More generally, the topic of sub-Riemannian geometry deals with the paths that objects may take when they are not free, and their movement is constrained in various ways.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] This article presents the mathematical formalism involved in defining, finding, and proving the existence of geodesics, in the case of Riemannian manifolds.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] The article Levi-Civita connection discusses the more general case of a pseudo-Riemannian manifold and geodesic (general relativity) discusses the special case of general relativity in greater detail.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] The most familiar examples are the straight lines in Euclidean geometry.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] On a sphere, the images of geodesics are the great circles.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] The shortest path from point *A* to point *B* on a sphere is given by the shorter arc of the great circle passing through *A* and *B*.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] If *A* and *B* are antipodal points, then there are *infinitely many* shortest paths between them.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] Geodesics on an ellipsoid behave in a more complicated way than on a sphere; in particular, they are not closed in general (see figure).
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] A **geodesic triangle** is formed by the geodesics joining each pair out of three points on a given surface.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] On the sphere, the geodesics are great circle arcs, forming a spherical triangle.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] In metric geometry, a geodesic is a curve which is everywhere locally a distance minimizer.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] This generalizes the notion of geodesic for Riemannian manifolds.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] If the last equality is satisfied for all *t*1, *t*2 ∈ *I*, the geodesic is called a **minimizing geodesic** or **shortest path**.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] In general, a metric space may have no geodesics, except constant curves.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] At the other extreme, any two points in a length metric space are joined by a minimizing sequence of rectifiable paths, although this minimizing sequence need not converge to a geodesic.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] The metric Hopf-Rinow theorem provides situations where a length space is automatically a geodesic space.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] Common examples of geodesic metric spaces that are often not manifolds include metric graphs, (locally compact) metric polyhedral complexes, infinite-dimensional pre-Hilbert spaces, and real trees.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] The distance $d(p,q)$ between two points p and q of M is defined as the infimum of the length taken over all continuous, piecewise continuously differentiable curves $\gamma :[a,b]\to M$ such that $\gamma (a)=p$ and $\gamma (b)=q$ .
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] In Riemannian geometry, all geodesics are locally distance-minimizing paths, but the converse is not true.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] In fact, only paths that are both locally distance minimizing and parameterized proportionately to arc-length are geodesics.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] All minima of E are also minima of L , but L is a bigger set since paths that are minima of L can be arbitrarily re-parameterized (without changing their length), while minima of E cannot.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] with equality if and only if $g(\gamma ',\gamma ')$ is equal to a constant a.e.; the path should be travelled at constant speed.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] It happens that minimizers of $E(\gamma )$ also minimize $L(\gamma )$ , because they turn out to be affinely parameterized, and the inequality is an equality.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] The usefulness of this approach is that the problem of seeking minimizers of E is a more robust variational problem.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] Indeed, $E(\gamma )$ is a "convex function" of $\gamma$ , so that within each isotopy class of "reasonable functions", one ought to expect existence, uniqueness, and regularity of minimizers.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] In contrast, "minimizers" of the functional $L(\gamma )$ are generally not very regular, because arbitrary reparameterizations are allowed.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] where $\Gamma _{\mu \nu }^{\lambda }$ are the Christoffel symbols of the metric.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] This is the **geodesic equation**, discussed below.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] Techniques of the classical calculus of variations can be applied to examine the energy functional E .
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] The critical points of the first variation are precisely the geodesics.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] In an appropriate sense, zeros of the second variation along a geodesic $\gamma$ arise along Jacobi fields.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] Jacobi fields are thus regarded as variations through geodesics.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] By applying variational techniques from classical mechanics, one can also regard geodesics as Hamiltonian flows.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] They are solutions of the associated Hamilton equations, with (pseudo-)Riemannian metric taken as Hamiltonian.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] at each point along the curve, where ${\dot {\gamma }}$ is the derivative with respect to t .
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] More precisely, in order to define the covariant derivative of ${\dot {\gamma }}$ it is necessary first to extend ${\dot {\gamma }}$ to a continuously differentiable vector field in an open set.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] However, the resulting value of (**1**) is independent of the choice of extension.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] where $\gamma ^{\mu }=x^{\mu }\circ \gamma (t)$ are the coordinates of the curve $\gamma (t)$ and $\Gamma _{\mu \nu }^{\lambda }$ are the Christoffel symbols of the connection $\nabla$ .
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] This is an ordinary differential equation for the coordinates.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] It has a unique solution, given an initial position and an initial velocity.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] Therefore, from the point of view of classical mechanics, geodesics can be thought of as trajectories of free particles in a manifold.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] Indeed, the equation $\nabla _{\dot {\gamma }}{\dot {\gamma }}=0$ means that the acceleration vector of the curve has no components in the direction of the surface (and therefore it is perpendicular to the tangent plane of the surface at each point of the curve).
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] So, the motion is completely determined by the bending of the surface.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] This is also the idea of general relativity where particles move on geodesics and the bending is caused by gravity.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] The *local existence and uniqueness theorem* for geodesics states that geodesics on a smooth manifold with an affine connection exist, and are unique.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] The proof of this theorem follows from the theory of ordinary differential equations, by noticing that the geodesic equation is a second-order ODE.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] Existence and uniqueness then follow from the Picard–Lindelöf theorem for the solutions of ODEs with prescribed initial conditions. γ depends smoothly on both *p* and *V*.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] In general, *I* may not be all of **R** as for example for an open disc in **R**2.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] Any γ extends to all of ℝ if and only if M is geodesically complete.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] Thus, *$G^{t}(V)=\exp(tV)$* is the exponential map of the vector *tV*.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] A closed orbit of the geodesic flow corresponds to a closed geodesic on *M*.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] On a (pseudo-)Riemannian manifold, the geodesic flow is identified with a Hamiltonian flow on the cotangent bundle.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] The Hamiltonian is then given by the inverse of the (pseudo-)Riemannian metric, evaluated against the canonical one-form.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] In particular the flow preserves the (pseudo-)Riemannian metric g , i.e.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] In particular, when *V* is a unit vector, $\gamma _{V}$ remains unit speed throughout, so the geodesic flow is tangent to the unit tangent bundle.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] Liouville's theorem implies invariance of a kinematic measure on the unit tangent bundle.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] The geodesic flow defines a family of curves in the tangent bundle.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] The derivatives of these curves define a vector field on the total space of the tangent bundle, known as the **geodesic spray**.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] The double tangent bundle can be visualized as the space of simultaneous changes of both the base point and velocity, without committing to any method to transport velocity across base points.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] For any $x\in M,\;v\in T_{x}M$ , the vertical fiber $V_{(x,v)}$ is determined by the projection map $\pi :TM\to M$ .
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] It consists of all ways to change the velocity v while fixing the base point x , and it is essentially a copy of $T_{x}M$ translated from $(x,0)$ to $(x,v)$ .
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] The affine connection then selects where $(x,v)$ would land under a change of base point while "fixing" velocity, which spans out the horizontal fiber $H_{(x,v)}$ .
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] at each point $x\in M,\;v\in T_{x}M$ , here $d\pi :TTM\to TM$ denotes the pushforward (differential) along the projection $\pi :TM\to M$ .
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] Intuitively, $d\pi$ discards the change to velocity and preserves change to base point.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] More generally, the same construction allows one to construct a vector field for any Ehresmann connection on the tangent bundle.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] It is not necessary that, if $u\in T_{x}M$ is also transported to $u'\in T_{x'}M$ , then $w+u$ must be transported $w'+u'$ .
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] Here *d*(*S*λ) is the pushforward along the scalar homothety $S_{\lambda }:X\mapsto \lambda X.$ A particular case of a non-linear connection arising in this manner is that associated to a Finsler manifold.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] Without equivariance under positive rescalings, vector transport along a directed path depends on the specific parameterization.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] where *a* and *b* are constant real numbers.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] Thus apart from specifying a certain class of embedded curves, the geodesic equation also determines a preferred class of parameterizations on each of the curves.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] Accordingly, solutions of (**1**) are called geodesics with **affine parameter**.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] An affine connection is *determined by* its family of affinely parameterized geodesics, up to torsion (Spivak 1999, Chapter 6, Addendum I).
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] The torsion itself does not, in fact, affect the family of geodesics, since the geodesic equation depends only on the symmetric part of the connection.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] is skew-symmetric, then $\nabla$ and ${\bar {\nabla }}$ have the same geodesics, with the same affine parameterizations.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] Furthermore, there is a unique connection having the same geodesics as $\nabla$ , but with vanishing torsion.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] Geodesics without a particular parameterization are described by a projective connection.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] Efficient solvers for the minimal geodesic problem on surfaces have been proposed by Mitchell, Kimmel, Crane, and others.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] A ribbon "test" is a way of finding a geodesic on a physical surface.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] The idea is to fit a bit of paper around a straight line (a ribbon) onto a curved surface as closely as possible without stretching or squishing the ribbon (without changing its internal geometry).
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] For example, when a ribbon is wound as a ring around a cone, the ribbon would not lie on the cone's surface but stick out, so that circle is not a geodesic on the cone.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] If the ribbon is adjusted so that all its parts touch the cone's surface, it would give an approximation to a geodesic.
[src:general-relativity/geodesic] While geometric in nature, the idea of a shortest path is so general that it easily finds extensive use in nearly all sciences, and in some other disciplines as well.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Gravitational waves transport energy as **gravitational radiation**, a form of radiant energy similar to electromagnetic radiation.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Newton's law of universal gravitation, part of classical mechanics, does not provide for their existence, instead asserting that gravity has instantaneous effect everywhere.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Gravitational waves therefore stand as an important relativistic phenomenon that is absent from Newtonian physics.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Gravitational-wave astronomy has the advantage that, unlike electromagnetic radiation, gravitational waves are not affected by intervening matter.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Sources that can be studied this way include binary star systems composed of white dwarfs, neutron stars, and black holes; events such as supernovae; and the formation of the early universe shortly after the Big Bang.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] The first indirect evidence for the existence of gravitational waves came in 1974 from the observed orbital decay of the Hulse–Taylor binary pulsar, which matched the decay predicted by general relativity for energy lost to gravitational radiation.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] In 1993, Russell Alan Hulse and Joseph Hooton Taylor Jr. received the Nobel Prize in Physics for this discovery.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] The first direct observation of gravitational waves was made in September 2015, when a signal generated by the merger of two black holes was received by the LIGO gravitational wave detectors in Livingston, Louisiana, and in Hanford, Washington.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] The 2017 Nobel Prize in Physics was subsequently awarded to Rainer Weiss, Kip Thorne and Barry Barish for their role in the direct detection of gravitational waves.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] In Albert Einstein's general theory of relativity, gravity is treated as a phenomenon resulting from the curvature of spacetime, which is caused by the presence of mass.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] If the masses move, the curvature of spacetime changes; and if the motion is not spherically symmetric, it can emit propagating curvature disturbances—i.e., gravitational waves—which radiate outward at the speed of light.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] A passing gravitational wave alters the relative separation of freely falling masses, reflecting a disturbance in local spacetime curvature.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] The separation varies in a pattern that mirrors the waveform of the disturbance.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] The magnitude of this effect is inversely proportional to the distance (not distance squared) from the source.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Inspiraling binary neutron stars are predicted to be a powerful source of gravitational waves as they coalesce, due to the very large acceleration of their masses as they orbit close to one another.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] However, due to the astronomical distances to these sources, the effects when measured on Earth are predicted to be very small, having strains of less than 1 part in 1020.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Scientists demonstrate the existence of these waves with highly-sensitive detectors at multiple observation sites.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] As of 2012, the LIGO and Virgo observatories were the most sensitive detectors, operating at resolutions of about one part in 5×1022.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] The Japanese detector KAGRA was completed in 2019; its first joint detection with LIGO and VIRGO was reported in 2021.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Another European ground-based detector, the Einstein Telescope, is under development.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] A space-based observatory, the Laser Interferometer Space Antenna (LISA), is also being developed by the European Space Agency.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Gravitational waves do not strongly interact with matter in the way that electromagnetic radiation does.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] This allows for the observation of events involving exotic objects in the distant universe that cannot be observed with more traditional means such as optical telescopes or radio telescopes; accordingly, gravitational wave astronomy gives new insights into the workings of the universe.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] In particular, gravitational waves could be of interest to cosmologists as they offer a possible way of observing the very early universe.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] This is not possible with conventional astronomy, since before recombination the universe was opaque to electromagnetic radiation.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Precise measurements of gravitational waves will also allow scientists to test more thoroughly the general theory of relativity.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] In principle, gravitational waves can exist at any frequency.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Very low frequency waves can be detected using pulsar timing arrays.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] In this technique, the timing of approximately 100 pulsars spread widely across the Milky Way is monitored over the course of years.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Detectable changes in the arrival time of their signals can result from passing gravitational waves generated by merging supermassive black holes (SMBH) with wavelengths measured in light-years.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] These timing changes can be used to locate the source of the waves.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Using this technique, astronomers have discovered the 'hum' of various SMBH mergers occurring in the universe.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Stephen Hawking and Werner Israel list different frequency bands for gravitational waves that could plausibly be detected, ranging from 10−7 Hz up to 1011 Hz.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] The speed of gravitational waves in the general theory of relativity is equal to the *speed of light* in vacuum, c.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Within the theory of special relativity, the constant c is not only about light; instead it is the highest possible speed for any interaction in nature.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Formally, c is a conversion factor for changing the unit of time to the unit of space.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] This makes it the only speed which does not depend either on the motion of an observer or a source of light and/or gravity.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Thus, the speed of "light" is also the speed of gravitational waves, and, further, the speed of any massless particle.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] In August 2017, the LIGO and Virgo detectors received a gravitational wave signal, GW170817, at nearly the same time as gamma ray satellites and optical telescopes received signals from its source in galaxy NGC 4993, about 130 million light years away.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] This measurement constrained the experimental difference between the speed of gravitational waves and light to be smaller than one part in 1015.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] The possibility of gravitational waves and that those might travel at the speed of light was discussed in 1893 by Oliver Heaviside, using the analogy between the inverse-square law of gravitation and the electrostatic force.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] In 1915 Einstein published his general theory of relativity, a complete relativistic theory of gravitation.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] He conjectured, like Poincaré, that the equation would produce gravitational waves, but, as he mentions in a letter to Schwarzschild in February 1916, these could not be similar to electromagnetic waves.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Electromagnetic waves can be produced by dipole motion, requiring both a positive and a negative charge.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Gravitation has no equivalent to negative charge.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Einstein continued to work through the complexity of the equations of general relativity to find an alternative wave model.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] However, the nature of Einstein's approximations led many (including Einstein himself) to doubt the result.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] In 1922, Arthur Eddington showed that two of Einstein's types of waves were artifacts of the coordinate system he used, and could be made to propagate at any speed by choosing appropriate coordinates, leading Eddington to jest that they "propagate at the speed of thought".
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] This also cast doubt on the physicality of the third (transverse–transverse) type that Eddington showed always propagate at the speed of light regardless of coordinate system.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] In 1936, Einstein and Nathan Rosen submitted a paper to *Physical Review* in which they claimed gravitational waves could not exist in the full general theory of relativity because any such solution of the field equations would have a singularity.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] The journal sent their manuscript to be reviewed by Howard P.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Robertson, who anonymously reported that the singularities in question were simply the harmless coordinate singularities of the employed cylindrical coordinates.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Einstein, who was unfamiliar with the concept of peer review, angrily withdrew the manuscript, never to publish in *Physical Review* again.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Nonetheless, his assistant Leopold Infeld, who had been in contact with Robertson, convinced Einstein that the criticism was correct, and the paper was rewritten with the opposite conclusion and published elsewhere.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] In 1956, Felix Pirani remedied the confusion caused by the use of various coordinate systems by rephrasing the gravitational waves in terms of the manifestly observable Riemann curvature tensor.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] At the time, Pirani's work was overshadowed by the community's focus on a different question: whether gravitational waves could transmit energy.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] This matter was settled by a thought experiment proposed by Richard Feynman during the first "GR" conference at Chapel Hill in 1957.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] In short, his argument known as the "sticky bead argument" notes that if one takes a rod with beads then the effect of a passing gravitational wave would be to move the beads along the rod; friction would then produce heat, implying that the passing wave had done work.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Shortly after, Hermann Bondi published a detailed version of the "sticky bead argument".
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] This later led to a series of articles (1959 to 1989) by Bondi and Pirani that established the existence of plane wave solutions for gravitational waves.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Paul Dirac further postulated the existence of gravitational waves, declaring them to have "physical significance" in his 1959 lecture at the Lindau Meetings.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Further, it was Dirac who predicted gravitational waves with a well-defined energy density in 1964.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] After the Chapel Hill conference, Joseph Weber started designing and building the first gravitational wave detectors now known as Weber bars.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] These doubts were strengthened when, by the mid-1970s, repeated experiments from other groups building their own Weber bars across the globe failed to find any signals, and by the late 1970s consensus was that Weber's results were spurious.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] In the same period, the first indirect evidence of gravitational waves was discovered.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] In 1974, Russell Alan Hulse and Joseph Hooton Taylor, Jr. discovered the first binary pulsar, which earned them the 1993 Nobel Prize in Physics.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Pulsar timing observations over the next decade showed a gradual decay of the orbital period of the Hulse–Taylor pulsar that matched the loss of energy and angular momentum in gravitational radiation predicted by general relativity.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] This indirect detection of gravitational waves motivated further searches, despite Weber's discredited result.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Some groups continued to improve Weber's original concept, while others pursued the detection of gravitational waves using laser interferometers.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] The idea of using a laser interferometer for this seems to have been floated independently by various people, including M.E.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] The first prototypes were developed in the 1970s by Robert L.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] In the decades that followed, ever more sensitive instruments were constructed, culminating in the construction of GEO600, LIGO, and Virgo.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] After years of producing null results, improved detectors became operational in 2015.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] On 11 February 2016, the LIGO-Virgo collaborations announced the first observation of gravitational waves, from a signal (dubbed GW150914) detected at 09:50:45 GMT on 14 September 2015 of two black holes with masses of 29 and 36 solar masses merging about 1.3 billion light-years away.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] During the final fraction of a second of the merger, it released more than 50 times the power of all the stars in the observable universe combined.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] The signal increased in frequency from 35 to 250 Hz over 10 cycles (5 orbits) as it rose in strength for a period of 0.2 second.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] The mass of the new merged black hole was 62 solar masses.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Energy equivalent to three solar masses was emitted as gravitational waves.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] The signal was seen by both LIGO detectors in Livingston and Hanford, with a time difference of 7 milliseconds due to the angle between the two detectors and the source.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] The signal came from the Southern Celestial Hemisphere, in the rough direction of (but much farther away than) the Magellanic Clouds.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] The confidence level of this being an observation of gravitational waves was 99.99994%.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] A year earlier, the BICEP2 collaboration claimed that they had detected the imprint of gravitational waves in the cosmic microwave background.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] However, they were later forced to retract this result.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] In 2017, the Nobel Prize in Physics was awarded to Rainer Weiss, Kip Thorne and Barry Barish for their role in the detection of gravitational waves.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] In 2023, results from pulsar timing arrays were announced suggesting evidence of a gravitational wave background.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Complex analysis of radio observations over 15 years of 67 pulsars showed correlations that matches the Hellings-Downs curve, consistent with a stochastic gravitational wave background.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Similar results are published by European Pulsar Timing Array, who claimed a $3\sigma$ -significance.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] The frequency dependence of this background radiation differs from models of the expected source, merging supermassive black hole binaries and other sources cannot yet be ruled out.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Gravitational waves are constantly passing Earth; however, even the strongest have a minuscule effect since their sources are generally at a great distance.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] This tiny effect from even extreme gravitational waves makes them observable on Earth only with the most sophisticated detectors.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] The effects of a passing gravitational wave, in an extremely exaggerated form, can be visualized by imagining a perfectly flat region of spacetime with a group of motionless test particles lying in a plane, e.g., the surface of a computer screen.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] As a gravitational wave passes through the particles along a line perpendicular to the plane of the particles, i.e., following the observer's line of vision into the screen, the particles will follow the distortion in spacetime, oscillating in a "cruciform" manner, as shown in the animations.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] The area enclosed by the test particles does not change and there is no motion along the direction of propagation.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] The oscillations depicted in the animation are exaggerated for the purpose of discussion – in reality a gravitational wave has a very small amplitude (as formulated in linearized gravity).
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] However, they help illustrate the kind of oscillations associated with gravitational waves as produced by a pair of masses in a circular orbit.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] In this case the amplitude of the gravitational wave is constant, but its plane of polarization changes or rotates at twice the orbital rate, so the time-varying gravitational wave size, or 'periodic spacetime strain', exhibits a variation as shown in the animation.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] If the orbit of the masses is elliptical then the gravitational wave's amplitude also varies with time according to Einstein's quadrupole formula.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] The speed, wavelength, and frequency of a gravitational wave are related by the equation *c* = *λf*, just like the equation for a light wave.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] For example, the animations shown here oscillate roughly once every two seconds.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] This would correspond to a frequency of 0.5 Hz, and a wavelength of about 600 000 km, or 47 times the diameter of the Earth.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] In the above example, it is assumed that the wave is linearly polarized with a "plus" polarization, written *h*+.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Polarization of a gravitational wave is just like polarization of a light wave except that the polarizations of a gravitational wave are 45 degrees apart, as opposed to 90 degrees.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] In particular, in a "cross"-polarized gravitational wave, *h*×, the effect on the test particles would be basically the same, but rotated by 45 degrees, as shown in the second animation.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Just as with light polarization, the polarizations of gravitational waves may also be expressed in terms of circularly polarized waves.
[src:general-relativity/gravitational-wave] Gravitational waves are polarized because of the nature of their source.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] The solution is a useful approximation for describing slowly rotating astronomical objects such as many stars and planets, including Earth and the Sun.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] It was found by Karl Schwarzschild and independently of him by Johannes Droste in 1916.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] According to Birkhoff's theorem, the Schwarzschild metric is the most general spherically symmetric vacuum solution of the Einstein field equations.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] A **Schwarzschild black hole** or **static black hole** is a black hole that has neither electric charge nor angular momentum (non-rotating).
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] A Schwarzschild black hole is described by the Schwarzschild metric, and cannot be distinguished from any other Schwarzschild black hole except by its mass.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] The Schwarzschild black hole is characterized by a surrounding spherical boundary, called the event horizon, which is situated at the Schwarzschild radius (⁠ $r_{\text{s}}$ ⁠), often called the radius of a black hole.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] The boundary is not a physical surface, and a person who fell through the event horizon (before being torn apart by tidal forces) would not notice any physical surface at that position; it is a mathematical surface which is significant in determining the black hole's properties.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] Any non-rotating and non-charged mass that is smaller than its Schwarzschild radius forms a black hole.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] The solution of the Einstein field equations is valid for any mass M, so in principle (within the theory of general relativity) a Schwarzschild black hole of any mass could exist if conditions became sufficiently favorable to allow for its formation.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] In the vicinity of a Schwarzschild black hole, space curves so much that even light rays are deflected, and very nearby light can be deflected so much that it travels several times around the black hole.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] The rotation group $\mathrm {SO} (3)=\mathrm {SO} (E^{3})$ acts on the $E^{3}-O$ or $S^{2}$ factor as rotations around the center O , while leaving the first $\mathbb {R}$ factor unchanged.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] The Schwarzschild metric is a solution of Einstein's field equations in empty space, meaning that it is valid only *outside* the gravitating body.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] That is, for a spherical body of radius R the solution is valid for $r>R$ .
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] To describe the gravitational field both inside and outside the gravitating body the Schwarzschild solution must be matched with some suitable interior solution at ⁠ $r=R$ ⁠, such as the interior Schwarzschild metric.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] The Schwarzschild metric has a singularity for *r* = 0, which is an intrinsic curvature singularity.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] It also seems to have a singularity on the event horizon *r* = *r*s.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] Depending on the point of view, the metric is therefore defined only on the exterior region $r>r_{\text{s}}$ , only on the interior region $r<r_{\text{s}}$ or their disjoint union.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] However, the metric is actually non-singular across the event horizon, as one sees in suitable coordinates (see below).
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] For ⁠ $r\gg r_{\text{s}}$ ⁠, the Schwarzschild metric is asymptotic to the standard Lorentz metric on Minkowski space.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] For almost all astrophysical objects, the ratio ${\frac {r_{\text{s}}}{R}}$ is extremely small.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] For example, the Schwarzschild radius $r_{\text{s}}^{({\text{Earth}})}$ of the Earth is roughly 8.9 mm, while the Sun, which is 3.3×105 times as massive has a Schwarzschild radius $r_{\text{s}}^{({\text{Sun}})}$ of approximately 3.0 km.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] The ratio becomes large only in close proximity to black holes and other ultra-dense objects such as neutron stars.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] The radial coordinate turns out to have physical significance as the "proper distance between two events that occur simultaneously relative to the radially moving geodesic clocks, the two events lying on the same radial coordinate line".
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] The Schwarzschild solution is analogous to a classical Newtonian theory of gravity that corresponds to the gravitational field around a point particle.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] Even at the surface of the Earth, the corrections to Newtonian gravity are only one part in a billion.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] However, this is enough for the metric to be used to correct for gravitational time dilation in the Global Positioning System.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] The Schwarzschild solution is named in honour of Karl Schwarzschild, who found the exact solution in 1915 and published it in January 1916, a little more than a month after the publication of Einstein's theory of general relativity.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] It was the first exact solution of the Einstein field equations other than the trivial flat space solution.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] Schwarzschild died shortly after his paper was published, as a result of a disease (thought to be pemphigus) he developed while serving in the German army during World War I.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] Johannes Droste in 1916 independently produced the same solution as Schwarzschild, using a simpler, more direct derivation.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] In the early years of general relativity there was a lot of confusion about the nature of the singularities found in the Schwarzschild and other solutions of the Einstein field equations.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] In Schwarzschild's original paper, he put what we now call the event horizon at the origin of his coordinate system.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] In this paper he also introduced what is now known as the Schwarzschild radial coordinate (r in the equations above), as an auxiliary variable.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] In his equations, Schwarzschild was using a different radial coordinate that was zero at the Schwarzschild radius.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] A more complete analysis of the singularity structure was given by David Hilbert in the following year, identifying the singularities both at *r* = 0 and *r* = *r*s.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] Although there was general consensus that the singularity at *r* = 0 was a 'genuine' physical singularity, the nature of the singularity at *r* = *r*s remained unclear.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] They, however, did not recognize that their solutions were just coordinate transforms, and in fact used their solution to argue that Einstein's theory was wrong.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] In 1924 Arthur Eddington produced the first coordinate transformation (Eddington–Finkelstein coordinates) that showed that the singularity at *r* = *r*s was a coordinate artifact, although he also seems to have been unaware of the significance of this discovery.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] Later, in 1932, Georges Lemaître gave a different coordinate transformation (Lemaître coordinates) to the same effect and was the first to recognize that this implied that the singularity at *r* = *r*s was not physical.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] In 1939 Howard Robertson showed that a free falling observer descending in the Schwarzschild metric would cross the *r* = *r*s singularity in a finite amount of proper time even though this would take an infinite amount of time in terms of coordinate time t.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] In 1950, John Synge produced a paper that showed the maximal analytic extension of the Schwarzschild metric, again showing that the singularity at *r* = *r*s was a coordinate artifact and that it represented two horizons.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] A similar result was later rediscovered by George Szekeres, and independently Martin Kruskal.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] The new coordinates nowadays known as Kruskal–Szekeres coordinates were much simpler than Synge's but both provided a single set of coordinates that covered the entire spacetime.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] However, perhaps due to the obscurity of the journals in which the papers of Lemaître and Synge were published their conclusions went unnoticed, with many of the major players in the field including Einstein believing that the singularity at the Schwarzschild radius was physical.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] Real progress was made in the 1960s when the mathematically rigorous formulation cast in terms of differential geometry entered the field of general relativity, allowing more exact definitions of what it means for a Lorentzian manifold to be singular.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] This led to definitive identification of the *r* = *r*s singularity in the Schwarzschild metric as an event horizon, i.e., a hypersurface in spacetime that can be crossed in only one direction.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] The Schwarzschild solution appears to have singularities at *r* = 0 and *r* = *r*s; some of the metric components "blow up" (entail division by zero or multiplication by infinity) at these radii.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] Since the Schwarzschild metric is expected to be valid only for those radii larger than the radius R of the gravitating body, there is no problem as long as *R* > *r*s.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] For ordinary stars and planets this is always the case.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] For example, the radius of the Sun is approximately 700000 km, while its Schwarzschild radius is only 3 km.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] The singularity at *r* = *r*s divides the Schwarzschild coordinates in two disconnected patches.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] The *exterior Schwarzschild solution* with *r* > *r*s is the one that is related to the gravitational fields of stars and planets.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] The *interior Schwarzschild solution* with 0 ≤ *r* < *r*s, which contains the singularity at *r* = 0, is completely separated from the outer patch by the singularity at *r* = *r*s.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] The Schwarzschild coordinates therefore give no physical connection between the two patches, which may be viewed as separate solutions.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] The singularity at *r* = *r*s is an illusion however; it is an instance of what is called a *coordinate singularity*.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] As the name implies, the singularity arises from a bad choice of coordinates or coordinate conditions.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] Using a different coordinate transformation one can then relate the extended external patch to the inner patch.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] If one asks that the solution be valid for all r one runs into a true physical singularity, or *gravitational singularity*, at the origin.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] To see that this is a true singularity one must look at quantities that are independent of the choice of coordinates.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] At *r* = 0 the curvature becomes infinite, indicating the presence of a singularity.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] At this point the metric cannot be extended in a smooth manner (the Kretschmann invariant involves second derivatives of the metric), spacetime itself is then no longer well-defined.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] Furthermore, Sbierski showed the metric cannot be extended even in a continuous manner.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] For a long time it was thought that such a solution was non-physical.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] However, a greater understanding of general relativity led to the realization that such singularities were a generic feature of the theory and not just an exotic special case.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] The Schwarzschild solution, taken to be valid for all *r* > 0, is called a Schwarzschild black hole.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] It is a perfectly valid solution of the Einstein field equations, although (like other black holes) it has rather bizarre properties.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] For *r* < *r*s the Schwarzschild radial coordinate r becomes timelike and the time coordinate t becomes spacelike.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] A curve at constant r is no longer a possible worldline of a particle or observer, not even if a force is exerted to try to keep it there; this occurs because spacetime has been curved so much that the direction of cause and effect (the particle's future light cone) points into the singularity.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] The surface *r* = *r*s demarcates what is called the *event horizon* of the black hole.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] It represents the point past which light can no longer escape the gravitational field.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] Any physical object whose radius R becomes less than or equal to the Schwarzschild radius has undergone gravitational collapse and become a black hole.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] The Schwarzschild solution can be expressed in a range of different choices of coordinates besides the Schwarzschild coordinates used above.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] Different choices tend to highlight different features of the solution.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] The table below shows some popular choices.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] In table above, some shorthand has been introduced for brevity.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] The speed of light c has been set to one.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] The notation $g_{\Omega }=d\theta ^{2}+\sin ^{2}\theta \,d\varphi ^{2}$ is used for the metric of a unit radius 2-dimensional sphere.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] Moreover, in each entry *R* and *T* denote alternative choices of radial and time coordinate for the particular coordinates.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] Note, the *R* or *T* may vary from entry to entry.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] The Kruskal–Szekeres coordinates have the form to which the Belinski–Zakharov transform can be applied.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] This implies that the Schwarzschild black hole is a form of gravitational soliton.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] The spatial curvature of the Schwarzschild solution for *r* > *r*s can be visualized as the graphic shows.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] Consider a constant time equatorial slice *H* through the Schwarzschild solution by fixing *θ* = ⁠π/2⁠, t = constant, and letting the remaining Schwarzschild coordinates (*r*, *φ*) vary.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] Imagine now that there is an additional Euclidean dimension w, which has no physical reality (it is not part of spacetime).
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] Thus, Flamm's paraboloid is useful for visualizing the spatial curvature of the Schwarzschild metric.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] It should not, however, be confused with a gravity well.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] No ordinary (massive or massless) particle can have a worldline lying on the paraboloid, since all distances on it are spacelike (this is a cross-section at one moment of time, so any particle moving on it would have an infinite velocity).
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] A tachyon could have a spacelike worldline that lies entirely on a single paraboloid.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] However, even in that case its geodesic path is not the trajectory one gets through a "rubber sheet" analogy of gravitational well: in particular, if the dimple is drawn pointing upward rather than downward, the tachyon's geodesic path still curves toward the central mass, not away.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] See the gravity well article for more information.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] Flamm's paraboloid may be derived as follows.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] A particle orbiting in the Schwarzschild metric can have a stable circular orbit with *r* > 3*r*s.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] Circular orbits with r between 1.5*r*s and 3*r*s are unstable, and no circular orbits exist for *r* < 1.5*r*s.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] The circular orbit of minimum radius 1.5*r*s corresponds to an orbital velocity approaching the speed of light.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] It is possible for a particle to have a constant value of r between *r*s and 1.5*r*s, but only if some force acts to keep it there.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] Noncircular orbits, such as Mercury's, dwell longer at small radii than would be expected in Newtonian gravity.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] This can be seen as a less extreme version of the more dramatic case in which a particle passes through the event horizon and dwells inside it forever.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] Intermediate between the case of Mercury and the case of an object falling past the event horizon, there are exotic possibilities such as knife-edge orbits, in which the satellite can be made to execute an arbitrarily large number of nearly circular orbits, after which it flies back outward.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] This is thus the subgroup of the ten-dimensional Poincaré group which takes the time axis (trajectory of the star) to itself.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] It omits the spatial translations (three dimensions) and boosts (three dimensions).
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] It retains the time translations (one dimension) and rotations (three dimensions).
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] Like the Poincaré group, it has four connected components: the component of the identity; the time reversed component; the spatial inversion component; and the component which is both time reversed and spatially inverted.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] The Ricci curvature scalar and the Ricci curvature tensor are both zero.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] 5.13 in Carroll and imply the other 6 by $R^{\alpha }{}_{\beta \gamma \delta }=g^{\alpha \kappa }g_{\beta \lambda }R^{\lambda }{}_{\kappa \delta \gamma }$ .
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] Components which are obtainable by other symmetries of the Riemann tensor are not displayed.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] To understand the physical meaning of these quantities, it is useful to express the curvature tensor in an orthonormal basis.
[src:general-relativity/schwarzschild-metric] These results are invariant to any Lorentz boost, thus the components do not change for non-static observers.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] In physics, **spacetime**, also called the **space-time continuum**, is a mathematical model that fuses the three dimensions of space and the one dimension of time into a single four-dimensional continuum.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Spacetime diagrams are useful in visualizing and understanding relativistic effects, such as how different observers perceive *where* and *when* events occur.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Until the turn of the 20th century, the assumption had been that the three-dimensional geometry of the universe (its description in terms of locations, shapes, distances, and directions) was distinct from time (the measurement of when events occur within the universe).
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] However, space and time took on new meanings with the Lorentz transformation and special theory of relativity.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] In 1908, Hermann Minkowski presented a geometric interpretation of special relativity that fused time and the three spatial dimensions into a single four-dimensional continuum now known as Minkowski space.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] This interpretation proved vital to the general theory of relativity, wherein spacetime is curved by mass and energy.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Non-relativistic classical mechanics treats time as a universal quantity of measurement that is uniform throughout, is separate from space, and is agreed on by all observers.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Classical mechanics assumes that time has a constant rate of passage, independent of the observer's state of motion, or anything external.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] It assumes that space is Euclidean: it assumes that space follows the geometry of common sense.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] In the context of special relativity, time cannot be separated from the three dimensions of space, because the observed rate at which time passes for an object depends on the object's velocity relative to the observer.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] General relativity provides an explanation of how gravitational fields can slow the passage of time for an object as seen by an observer outside the field.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] In ordinary space, a position is specified by three numbers, known as dimensions.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] In the Cartesian coordinate system, these are often called *x*, *y* and *z*.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] A point in spacetime is called an *event*, and requires four numbers to be specified: the three-dimensional location in space, plus the position in time (Fig.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] An event is represented by a set of coordinates *x*, *y*, *z* and *t*.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Unlike the analogies used in popular writings to explain events, such as firecrackers or sparks, mathematical events have zero duration and represent a single point in spacetime.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Although it is possible to be in motion relative to the popping of a firecracker or a spark, it is not possible for an observer to be in motion relative to an event.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The path of a particle through spacetime can be considered to be a sequence of events.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The series of events can be linked together to form a curve that represents the particle's progress through spacetime.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] That path is called the particle's *world line*.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Mathematically, spacetime is a *manifold*, which is to say, it appears locally "flat" near each point in the same way that, at small enough scales, the surface of a globe appears to be flat.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] A scale factor, c (conventionally called the *speed-of-light*) relates distances measured in space to distances measured in time.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] It was only with the advent of sensitive scientific measurements in the mid-1800s, such as the Fizeau experiment and the Michelson–Morley experiment, that puzzling discrepancies began to be noted between observation versus predictions based on the implicit assumption of Euclidean space.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] In special relativity, an observer will, in most cases, mean a frame of reference from which a set of objects or events is being measured.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] This usage differs significantly from the ordinary English meaning of the term.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Reference frames are inherently nonlocal constructs, and according to this usage of the term, it does not make sense to speak of an observer as having a location.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] 1-1, imagine that the frame under consideration is equipped with a dense lattice of clocks, synchronized within this reference frame, that extends indefinitely throughout the three dimensions of space.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Any specific location within the lattice is not important.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The latticework of clocks is used to determine the time and position of events taking place within the whole frame.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The term *observer* refers to the whole ensemble of clocks associated with one inertial frame of reference.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] In this idealized case, every point in space has a clock associated with it, and thus the clocks register each event instantly, with no time delay between an event and its recording.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] A real observer will see a delay between the emission of a signal and its detection due to the speed of light.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] To synchronize the clocks, in the data reduction following an experiment, the time when a signal is received will be corrected to reflect its actual time were it to have been recorded by an idealized lattice of clocks.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] In many books on special relativity, especially older ones, the word "observer" is used in the more ordinary sense of the word.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] It is usually clear from context which meaning has been adopted.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Physicists distinguish between what one *measures* or *observes*, after one has factored out signal propagation delays, versus what one visually sees without such corrections.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Failing to understand the difference between what one measures and what one sees is the source of much confusion among students of relativity.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Michelson and Morley expected that motion through the aether would cause a differential phase shift between light traversing the two arms of their apparatus.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The most logical explanation of their negative result, aether dragging, was in conflict with the observation of stellar aberration.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] By the mid-1800s, various experiments such as the observation of the Arago spot and differential measurements of the speed of light in air versus water were considered to have proven the wave nature of light as opposed to a corpuscular theory.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Propagation of waves was then assumed to require the existence of a *waving* medium; in the case of light waves, this was considered to be a hypothetical luminiferous aether.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The various attempts to establish the properties of this hypothetical medium yielded contradictory results.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] For example, the Fizeau experiment of 1851, conducted by French physicist Hippolyte Fizeau, demonstrated that the speed of light in flowing water was less than the sum of the speed of light in air plus the speed of the water by an amount dependent on the water's index of refraction.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Among other issues, the dependence of the partial aether-dragging implied by this experiment on the index of refraction (which is dependent on wavelength) led to the unpalatable conclusion that aether *simultaneously* flows at different speeds for different colors of light.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The Michelson–Morley experiment of 1887 (Fig.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] 1-2) showed no differential influence of Earth's motions through the hypothetical aether on the speed of light, and the most likely explanation, complete aether dragging, was in conflict with the observation of stellar aberration.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] No length changes occur in directions transverse to the direction of motion.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] By 1904, Lorentz had expanded his theory such that he had arrived at equations formally identical with those that Einstein was to derive later, i.e. the Lorentz transformation.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] As a theory of dynamics (the study of forces and torques and their effect on motion), his theory assumed actual physical deformations of the physical constituents of matter.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Lorentz's equations predicted a quantity that he called *local time*, with which he could explain the aberration of light, the Fizeau experiment and other phenomena.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Henri Poincaré was the first to combine space and time into spacetime.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] He argued in 1898 that the simultaneity of two events is a matter of convention.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] In 1900, he recognized that Lorentz's "local time" is actually what is indicated by moving clocks by applying an explicitly *operational definition* of clock synchronization assuming constant light speed.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] In 1900 and 1904, he suggested the inherent undetectability of the aether by emphasizing the validity of what he called the principle of relativity.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] In 1905/1906 he mathematically perfected Lorentz's theory of electrons in order to bring it into accordance with the postulate of relativity.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] While discussing various hypotheses on Lorentz invariant gravitation, he introduced the innovative concept of a 4-dimensional spacetime by defining various four-vectors, namely four-position, four-velocity, and four-force.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] He did not pursue the 4-dimensional formalism in subsequent papers, however, stating that this line of research seemed to "entail great pain for limited profit", ultimately concluding "that three-dimensional language seems the best suited to the description of our world".
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Even as late as 1909, Poincaré continued to describe the dynamical interpretation of the Lorentz transform.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] In 1905, Albert Einstein analyzed special relativity in terms of kinematics (the study of moving bodies without reference to forces) rather than dynamics.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] His results were mathematically equivalent to those of Lorentz and Poincaré.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] He obtained them by recognizing that the entire theory can be built upon two postulates: the principle of relativity and the principle of the constancy of light speed.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] His work was filled with vivid imagery involving the exchange of light signals between clocks in motion, careful measurements of the lengths of moving rods, and other such examples.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] By using the mass–energy equivalence, Einstein showed that the gravitational mass of a body is proportional to its energy content, which was one of the early results in developing general relativity.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] While it would appear that he did not at first think geometrically about spacetime, in the further development of general relativity, Einstein fully incorporated the spacetime formalism.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] When Einstein published in 1905, another of his competitors, his former mathematics professor Hermann Minkowski, had also arrived at most of the basic elements of special relativity.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Minkowski had been concerned with the state of electrodynamics after Michelson's disruptive experiments at least since the summer of 1905, when Minkowski and David Hilbert led an advanced seminar attended by notable physicists of the time to study the papers of Lorentz, Poincaré et al.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Minkowski saw Einstein's work as an extension of Lorentz's, and was most directly influenced by Poincaré.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] On 5 November 1907 (a little more than a year before his death), Minkowski introduced his geometric interpretation of spacetime in a lecture to the Göttingen Mathematical society with the title, *The Relativity Principle* (*Das Relativitätsprinzip*).
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] On 21 September 1908, Minkowski presented his talk, *Space and Time* (*Raum und Zeit*), to the German Society of Scientists and Physicians.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] 1-4), and included a remarkable demonstration that the concept of the *invariant interval* (discussed below), along with the empirical observation that the speed of light is finite, allows derivation of the entirety of special relativity.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The spacetime concept and the Lorentz group are closely connected to certain types of sphere, hyperbolic, or conformal geometries and their transformation groups already developed in the 19th century, in which invariant intervals analogous to the spacetime interval are used.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Einstein, for his part, was initially dismissive of Minkowski's geometric interpretation of special relativity, regarding it as *überflüssige Gelehrsamkeit* (superfluous learnedness).
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] However, in order to complete his search for general relativity that started in 1907, the geometric interpretation of relativity proved to be vital.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] In 1916, Einstein fully acknowledged his indebtedness to Minkowski, whose interpretation greatly facilitated the transition to general relativity.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Although two viewers may measure the *x*, *y*, and *z* position of the two points using different coordinate systems, the distance between the points will be the same for both, assuming that they are measuring using the same units.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] In special relativity, however, the distance between two points is no longer the same if measured by two different observers, when one of the observers is moving, because of Lorentz contraction.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The situation is even more complicated if the two points are separated in time as well as in space.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Thus, a different measure must be used to measure the effective "distance" between two events.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] In four-dimensional spacetime, the analog to distance is the interval.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Although time comes in as a fourth dimension, it is treated differently than the spatial dimensions.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Minkowski space hence differs in important respects from four-dimensional Euclidean space.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Special relativity provides a new invariant, called the **spacetime interval**, which combines distances in space and in time.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] All observers who measure the time and distance between any two events will end up computing the same spacetime interval.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The constant $c,$ the speed of light, converts time t units (like seconds) into space units (like meters).
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The squared interval $\Delta s^{2}$ is a measure of separation between events A and B that are time separated and in addition space separated either because there are two separate objects undergoing events, or because a single object in space is moving inertially between its events.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The separation interval is the difference between the square of the spatial distance separating event B from event A and the square of the spatial distance traveled by a light signal in that same time interval $\Delta t$ .
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] If the event separation is due to a light signal, then this difference vanishes and $\Delta s=0$ .
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] In a different inertial frame, say with coordinates $(t',x',y',z')$ , the spacetime interval $ds'$ can be written in a same form as above.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Because of the constancy of speed of light, the light events in all inertial frames belong to zero interval, $ds=ds'=0$ .
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] For any other infinitesimal event where $ds\neq 0$ , one can prove that $ds^{2}=ds'^{2}$ which in turn upon integration leads to $s=s'$ .
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The invariance of the spacetime interval between the same events for all inertial frames of reference is one of the fundamental results of special theory of relativity.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Although for brevity, one frequently sees interval expressions expressed without deltas, including in most of the following discussion, it should be understood that in general, x means $\Delta {x}$ , etc.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] We are always concerned with *differences* of spatial or temporal coordinate values belonging to two events, and since there is no preferred origin, single coordinate values have no essential meaning.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The equation above is similar to the Pythagorean theorem, except with a minus sign between the $(ct)^{2}$ and the $x^{2}$ terms.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The spacetime interval is the quantity $s^{2},$ not s itself.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The reason is that unlike distances in Euclidean geometry, intervals in Minkowski spacetime can be negative.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Rather than deal with square roots of negative numbers, physicists customarily regard $s^{2}$ as a distinct symbol in itself, rather than the square of something.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] A minor variation is to place the time coordinate last rather than first.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Both conventions are widely used within the field of study.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] In the following discussion, we use the first convention.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] In general $s^{2}$ can assume any real number value.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] If $s^{2}$ is positive, the spacetime interval is referred to as **timelike**.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Since spatial distance traversed by any massive object is always less than distance traveled by the light for the same time interval, positive intervals are always timelike.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] If $s^{2}$ is negative, the spacetime interval is said to be **spacelike**.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Spacetime intervals are equal to zero when $x=\pm ct.$ In other words, the spacetime interval between two events on the world line of something moving at the speed of light is zero.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Such an interval is termed **lightlike** or **null**.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] A photon arriving in our eye from a distant star will not have aged, despite having (from our perspective) spent years in its passage.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] A spacetime diagram is typically drawn with only a single space and a single time coordinate.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] 2-1 presents a spacetime diagram illustrating the world lines (i.e. paths in spacetime) of two photons, A and B, originating from the same event and going in opposite directions.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] In addition, C illustrates the world line of a slower-than-light-speed object.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The vertical time coordinate is scaled by c so that it has the same units (meters) as the horizontal space coordinate.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Since photons travel at the speed of light, their world lines have a slope of ±1.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] In other words, every meter that a photon travels to the left or right requires approximately 3.3 nanoseconds of time.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] 2-2, two Galilean reference frames (i.e. conventional 3-space frames) are displayed in relative motion.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Frame S belongs to a first observer O, and frame S′ (pronounced "S prime") belongs to a second observer O′.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] 2-3b illustrates a *relativistic* spacetime diagram from the viewpoint of observer O.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Since S and S′ are in standard configuration, their origins coincide at times *t* = 0 in frame S and *t*′ = 0 in frame S′.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The ct′ axis passes through the events in frame S′ which have *x*′ = 0.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] But the points with *x*′ = 0 are moving in the *x*-direction of frame S with velocity *v*, so that they are not coincident with the *ct* axis at any time other than zero.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The *x*′ axis is also tilted with respect to the *x* axis.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] To determine the angle of this tilt, we recall that the slope of the world line of a light pulse is always ±1.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] 2-3c presents a spacetime diagram from the viewpoint of observer O′.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Event P represents the emission of a light pulse at *x*′ = 0, *ct*′ = −*a*.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The pulse is reflected from a mirror situated at distance *a* from the light source (event Q), and returns to the light source at *x*′ = 0, *ct*′ = *a* (event R).
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The same events P, Q, R are plotted in Fig.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The light paths have slopes = 1 and −1, so that △PQR forms a right triangle with PQ and QR both at 45 degrees to the *x* and *ct* axes.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Since OP = OQ = OR, the angle between x′ and x must also be *θ*.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] While the rest frame has space and time axes that meet at right angles, the moving frame is drawn with axes that meet at an acute angle.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] 2–4, event O is at the origin of a spacetime diagram, and the two diagonal lines represent all events that have zero spacetime interval with respect to the origin event.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] These two lines form what is called the *light cone* of the event O, since adding a second spatial dimension (Fig.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] 2-5) makes the appearance that of two right circular cones meeting with their apices at O.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] One cone extends into the future (t>0), the other into the past (t<0).
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] A light (double) cone divides spacetime into separate regions with respect to its apex.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The interior of the future light cone consists of all events that are separated from the apex by more *time* (temporal distance) than necessary to cross their *spatial distance* at lightspeed; these events comprise the *timelike future* of the event O.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Likewise, the *timelike past* comprises the interior events of the past light cone.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] So in *timelike intervals* Δ*ct* is greater than Δ*x*, making timelike intervals positive.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The region exterior to the light cone consists of events that are separated from the event O by more *space* than can be crossed at lightspeed in the given *time*.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] These events comprise the so-called *spacelike* region of the event O, denoted "Elsewhere" in Fig.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Events on the light cone itself are said to be *lightlike* (or *null separated*) from O.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Because of the invariance of the spacetime interval, all observers will assign the same light cone to any given event, and thus will agree on this division of spacetime.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The light cone has an essential role within the concept of causality.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] It is possible for a not-faster-than-light-speed signal to travel from the position and time of O to the position and time of D (Fig.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] It is hence possible for event O to have a causal influence on event D.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The future light cone contains all the events that could be causally influenced by O.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Likewise, it is possible for a not-faster-than-light-speed signal to travel from the position and time of A, to the position and time of O.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The past light cone contains all the events that could have a causal influence on O.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] In contrast, assuming that signals cannot travel faster than the speed of light, any event, like e.g.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] B or C, in the spacelike region (Elsewhere), cannot either affect event O, nor can they be affected by event O employing such signalling.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Under this assumption any causal relationship between event O and any events in the spacelike region of a light cone is excluded.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] All observers will agree that for any given event, an event within the given event's future light cone occurs *after* the given event.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Likewise, for any given event, an event within the given event's past light cone occurs *before* the given event.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The before–after relationship observed for timelike-separated events remains unchanged no matter what the reference frame of the observer, i.e. no matter how the observer may be moving.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The situation is quite different for spacelike-separated events.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] 2-4** was drawn from the reference frame of an observer moving at *v* = 0.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] From this reference frame, event C is observed to occur after event O, and event B is observed to occur before event O.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] From a different reference frame, the orderings of these non-causally-related events can be reversed.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] In particular, one notes that if two events are simultaneous in a particular reference frame, they are *necessarily* separated by a spacelike interval and thus are noncausally related.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The observation that simultaneity is not absolute, but depends on the observer's reference frame, is termed the relativity of simultaneity.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] 2-6 illustrates the use of spacetime diagrams in the analysis of the relativity of simultaneity.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The events in spacetime are invariant, but the coordinate frames transform as discussed above for Fig.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The three events (A, B, C) are simultaneous from the reference frame of an observer moving at *v* = 0.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] From the reference frame of an observer moving at *v* = 0.3*c*, the events appear to occur in the order C, B, A.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] From the reference frame of an observer moving at *v* = −0.5*c*, the events appear to occur in the order A, B, C.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The white line represents a *plane of simultaneity* being moved from the past of the observer to the future of the observer, highlighting events residing on it.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The gray area is the light cone of the observer, which remains invariant.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] A spacelike spacetime interval gives the same distance that an observer would measure if the events being measured were simultaneous to the observer.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] A spacelike spacetime interval hence provides a measure of *proper distance*, i.e. the true distance = ${\sqrt {-s^{2}}}.$ Likewise, a timelike spacetime interval gives the same measure of time as would be presented by the cumulative ticking of a clock that moves along a given world line.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] In Euclidean space (having spatial dimensions only), the set of points equidistant (using the Euclidean metric) from some point form a circle (in two dimensions) or a sphere (in three dimensions).
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] with $s^{2}$ some positive real constant.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] These equations describe two families of hyperbolae in an *x*–*ct* spacetime diagram, which are termed *invariant hyperbolae*.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] 2-7a, each magenta hyperbola connects all events having some fixed spacelike separation from the origin, while the green hyperbolae connect events of equal timelike separation.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] On the other hand, the green hyperbolae, which cross the *ct* axis, are spacelike curves because all intervals *along* these hyperbolae are spacelike intervals: No causality is possible between any two points on one of these hyperbolae, because all secants represent speeds larger than c .
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] 2-7b reflects the situation in (1+2)-dimensional Minkowski spacetime (one temporal and two spatial dimensions) with the corresponding hyperboloids.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The invariant hyperbolae displaced by spacelike intervals from the origin generate hyperboloids of one sheet, while the invariant hyperbolae displaced by timelike intervals from the origin generate hyperboloids of two sheets.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The (1+2)-dimensional boundary between space- and time-like hyperboloids, established by the events forming a zero spacetime interval to the origin, is made up by degenerating the hyperboloids to the light cone.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] In (1+1)-dimensions the hyperbolae degenerate to the two grey 45°-lines depicted in Fig.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] 2-8 illustrates the invariant hyperbola for all events that can be reached from the origin in a proper time of 5 meters (approximately 1.67×10−8 s).
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Different world lines represent clocks moving at different speeds.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] A clock that is stationary with respect to the observer has a world line that is vertical, and the elapsed time measured by the observer is the same as the proper time.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] For a clock traveling at 0.3 *c*, the elapsed time measured by the observer is 5.24 meters (1.75×10−8 s), while for a clock traveling at 0.7 *c*, the elapsed time measured by the observer is 7.00 meters (2.34×10−8 s).
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] This illustrates the phenomenon known as time dilation.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Clocks that travel faster take longer (in the observer frame) to tick out the same amount of proper time, and they travel further along the x–axis within that proper time than they would have without time dilation.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The measurement of time dilation by two observers in different inertial reference frames is mutual.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] If observer O measures the clocks of observer O′ as running slower in his frame, observer O′ in turn will measure the clocks of observer O as running slower.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Length contraction, like time dilation, is a manifestation of the relativity of simultaneity.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Measurement of length requires measurement of the spacetime interval between two events that are simultaneous in one's frame of reference.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] But events that are simultaneous in one frame of reference are, in general, not simultaneous in other frames of reference.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] 2-9 illustrates the motions of a 1 m rod that is traveling at 0.5 *c* along the *x* axis.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The edges of the blue band represent the world lines of the rod's two endpoints.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The invariant hyperbola illustrates events separated from the origin by a spacelike interval of 1 m.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The endpoints O and B measured when *t*′ = 0 are simultaneous events in the S′ frame.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] But to an observer in frame S, events O and B are not simultaneous.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] To measure length, the observer in frame S measures the endpoints of the rod as projected onto the *x*-axis along their world lines.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The projection of the rod's *world sheet* onto the *x* axis yields the foreshortened length OC.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] (not illustrated) Drawing a vertical line through A so that it intersects the *x*′ axis demonstrates that, even as OB is foreshortened from the point of view of observer O, OA is likewise foreshortened from the point of view of observer O′.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] In the same way that each observer measures the other's clocks as running slow, each observer measures the other's rulers as being contracted.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] In regards to mutual length contraction, **Fig.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] 2-9** illustrates that the primed and unprimed frames are mutually rotated by a hyperbolic angle (analogous to ordinary angles in Euclidean geometry).
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Because of this rotation, the projection of a primed meter-stick onto the unprimed *x*-axis is foreshortened, while the projection of an unprimed meter-stick onto the primed x′-axis is likewise foreshortened.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] Mutual time dilation and length contraction tend to strike beginners as inherently self-contradictory concepts.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] If an observer in frame S measures a clock, at rest in frame S', as running slower than his', while S' is moving at speed *v* in S, then the principle of relativity requires that an observer in frame S' likewise measures a clock in frame S, moving at speed −*v* in S', as running slower than hers.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] This apparent contradiction stems from not correctly taking into account the different settings of the necessary, related measurements.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] These settings allow for a consistent explanation of the *only apparent* contradiction.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] It is not about the abstract ticking of two identical clocks, but about how to measure in one frame the temporal distance of two ticks of a moving clock.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] It turns out that in mutually observing the duration between ticks of clocks, each moving in the respective frame, different sets of clocks must be involved.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] In order to measure in frame S the tick duration of a moving clock W′ (at rest in S′), one uses *two* additional, synchronized clocks W1 and W2 at rest in two arbitrarily fixed points in S with the spatial distance *d*.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] For both events the two readings of the collocated clocks are recorded.
[src:general-relativity/spacetime-p01] The difference of the two readings of W′ is the temporal distance of the two events in S′.
